#. type: Content of: <guide><chapter><title>
#: en/articles/lpi-101-administration-p2.xml:115
#, no-wrap
msgid "Regular Expressions"
msgstr ""

#. type: Content of: <guide><chapter><section><title>
#: en/articles/lpi-101-administration-p2.xml:117
#, no-wrap
msgid "What is a regular expression?"
msgstr ""

#. type: Content of: <guide><chapter><section><body><p>
#: en/articles/lpi-101-administration-p2.xml:121
#, no-wrap
msgid ""
"A regular expression (also called a \"regex\" or \"regexp\") is a special syntax\n"
"used to describe text patterns. On Linux systems, regular expressions are\n"
"commonly used to find patterns of text, as well as to perform\n"
"search-and-replace operations on text streams.\n"
msgstr ""

#. type: Content of: <guide><chapter><section><title>
#: en/articles/lpi-101-administration-p2.xml:130
#, no-wrap
msgid "Glob comparison"
msgstr ""

#. type: Content of: <guide><chapter><section><body><p>
#: en/articles/lpi-101-administration-p2.xml:134
#, no-wrap
msgid ""
"As we take a look at regular expressions, you may find that regular expression\n"
"syntax looks similar to the filename \"globbing\" syntax that we looked at in\n"
"Part 1. However, don't let this fool you; their similarity is only skin deep.\n"
"Both regular expressions and filename globbing patterns, while they may look\n"
"similar, are fundamentally different beasts.\n"
msgstr ""

#. type: Content of: <guide><chapter><section><title>
#: en/articles/lpi-101-administration-p2.xml:144
#, no-wrap
msgid "The simple substring"
msgstr ""

#. type: Content of: <guide><chapter><section><body><p>
#: en/articles/lpi-101-administration-p2.xml:148
#, no-wrap
msgid ""
"With that caution, let's take a look at the most basic of regular expressions,\n"
"the simple substring. To do this, we're going to use <c>grep</c>, a command\n"
"that scans the contents of a file for a particular regular expression. grep\n"
"prints every line that matches the regular expression, and ignores every line\n"
"that doesn't:\n"
msgstr ""

#. type: Attribute 'caption' of: <guide><chapter><section><body><pre>
#: en/articles/lpi-101-administration-p2.xml:155
#, no-wrap
msgid "grep in action"
msgstr ""

#. type: Content of: <guide><chapter><section><body><pre>
#: en/articles/lpi-101-administration-p2.xml:156
#, no-wrap
msgid ""
"$ <i>grep bash /etc/passwd</i>\n"
"operator:x:11:0:operator:/root:/bin/bash\n"
"root:x:0:0::/root:/bin/bash\n"
"ftp:x:40:1::/home/ftp:/bin/bash\n"
msgstr ""

#. type: Content of: <guide><chapter><section><body><p>
#: en/articles/lpi-101-administration-p2.xml:163
#, no-wrap
msgid ""
"Above, the first parameter to <c>grep</c> is a regex; the second is a filename.\n"
"<c>grep</c> read each line in /etc/passwd and applied the simple substring\n"
"regex bash to it, looking for a match. If a match was found, <c>grep</c>\n"
"printed out the entire line; otherwise, the line was ignored.\n"
msgstr ""

#. type: Content of: <guide><chapter><section><title>
#: en/articles/lpi-101-administration-p2.xml:172
#, no-wrap
msgid "Understanding the simple substring"
msgstr ""

#. type: Content of: <guide><chapter><section><body><p>
#: en/articles/lpi-101-administration-p2.xml:176
#, no-wrap
msgid ""
"In general, if you are searching for a substring, you can just specify the text\n"
"verbatim without supplying any \"special\" characters. The only time you'd need\n"
"to do anything special would be if your substring contained a +, ., *, [, ], or\n"
"\\, in which case these characters would need to be enclosed in quotes and\n"
"preceded by a backslash. Here are a few more examples of simple substring\n"
"regular expressions:\n"
msgstr ""

#. type: Content of: <guide><chapter><section><body><ul><li>
#: en/articles/lpi-101-administration-p2.xml:185
#, no-wrap
msgid "/tmp (scans for the literal string /tmp)"
msgstr ""

#. type: Content of: <guide><chapter><section><body><ul><li>
#: en/articles/lpi-101-administration-p2.xml:186
#, no-wrap
msgid "\"\\[box\\]\" (scans for the literal string [box])"
msgstr ""

#. type: Content of: <guide><chapter><section><body><ul><li>
#: en/articles/lpi-101-administration-p2.xml:187
#, no-wrap
msgid "\"\\*funny\\*\" (scans for the literal string *funny*)"
msgstr ""

#. type: Content of: <guide><chapter><section><body><ul><li>
#: en/articles/lpi-101-administration-p2.xml:188
#, no-wrap
msgid "\"ld\\.so\" (scans for the literal string ld.so)"
msgstr ""

#. type: Content of: <guide><chapter><section><title>
#: en/articles/lpi-101-administration-p2.xml:194
#, no-wrap
msgid "Metacharacters"
msgstr ""

#. type: Content of: <guide><chapter><section><body><p>
#: en/articles/lpi-101-administration-p2.xml:198
#, no-wrap
msgid ""
"With regular expressions, you can perform much more complex searches than the\n"
"examples we've looked at so far by taking advantage of metacharacters. One of\n"
"these metacharacters is the . (a period), which matches any single character:\n"
msgstr ""

#. type: Attribute 'caption' of: <guide><chapter><section><body><pre>
#: en/articles/lpi-101-administration-p2.xml:203
#, no-wrap
msgid "The period metacharacter"
msgstr ""

#. type: Content of: <guide><chapter><section><body><pre>
#: en/articles/lpi-101-administration-p2.xml:204
#, no-wrap
msgid ""
"$ <i>grep dev.hda /etc/fstab</i>\n"
"/dev/hda3       /               reiserfs        noatime,ro 1 1\n"
"/dev/hda1       /boot           reiserfs        noauto,noatime,notail 1 2\n"
"/dev/hda2       swap            swap            sw 0 0\n"
"#/dev/hda4      /mnt/extra      reiserfs        noatime,rw 1 1\n"
msgstr ""

#. type: Content of: <guide><chapter><section><body><p>
#: en/articles/lpi-101-administration-p2.xml:212
#, no-wrap
msgid ""
"In this example, the literal text dev.hda didn't appear on any of the lines in\n"
"/etc/fstab. However, grep wasn't scanning them for the literal dev.hda string,\n"
"but for the dev.hda pattern. Remember that the . will match any single\n"
"character. As you can see, the . metacharacter is functionally equivalent to\n"
"how the ? metacharacter works in \"glob\" expansions.\n"
msgstr ""

#. type: Content of: <guide><chapter><section><title>
#: en/articles/lpi-101-administration-p2.xml:222
#, no-wrap
msgid "Using []"
msgstr ""

#. type: Content of: <guide><chapter><section><body><p>
#: en/articles/lpi-101-administration-p2.xml:226
#, no-wrap
msgid ""
"If we wanted to match a character a bit more specifically than ., we could use\n"
"[ and ] (square brackets) to specify a subset of characters that should be\n"
"matched:\n"
msgstr ""

#. type: Attribute 'caption' of: <guide><chapter><section><body><pre>
#: en/articles/lpi-101-administration-p2.xml:231
#, no-wrap
msgid "Brackets in action"
msgstr ""

#. type: Content of: <guide><chapter><section><body><pre>
#: en/articles/lpi-101-administration-p2.xml:232
#, no-wrap
msgid ""
"$ <i>grep dev.hda[12] /etc/fstab</i>\n"
"/dev/hda1       /boot           reiserfs        noauto,noatime,notail 1 2\n"
"/dev/hda2       swap            swap            sw 0 0\n"
msgstr ""

#. type: Content of: <guide><chapter><section><body><p>
#: en/articles/lpi-101-administration-p2.xml:238
#, no-wrap
msgid ""
"As you can see, this particular syntactical feature works identically to the []\n"
"in \"glob\" filename expansions. Again, this is one of the tricky things about\n"
"learning regular expressions -- the syntax is similar but not identical to\n"
"\"glob\" filename expansion syntax, which often makes regexes a bit confusing to\n"
"learn.\n"
msgstr ""

#. type: Content of: <guide><chapter><section><title>
#: en/articles/lpi-101-administration-p2.xml:248
#, no-wrap
msgid "Using [^]"
msgstr ""

#. type: Content of: <guide><chapter><section><body><p>
#: en/articles/lpi-101-administration-p2.xml:252
#, no-wrap
msgid ""
"You can reverse the meaning of the square brackets by putting a ^ immediately\n"
"after the [. In this case, the brackets will match any character that is\n"
"<e>not</e> listed inside the brackets. Again, note that we use [^] with regular\n"
"expressions, but [!] with globs:\n"
msgstr ""

#. type: Attribute 'caption' of: <guide><chapter><section><body><pre>
#: en/articles/lpi-101-administration-p2.xml:258
#, no-wrap
msgid "Brackets with negation"
msgstr ""

#. type: Content of: <guide><chapter><section><body><pre>
#: en/articles/lpi-101-administration-p2.xml:259
#, no-wrap
msgid ""
"$ <i>grep dev.hda[^12] /etc/fstab</i>\n"
"/dev/hda3       /               reiserfs        noatime,ro 1 1\n"
"#/dev/hda4      /mnt/extra      reiserfs        noatime,rw 1 1\n"
msgstr ""

#. type: Content of: <guide><chapter><section><title>
#: en/articles/lpi-101-administration-p2.xml:267
#, no-wrap
msgid "Differing syntax"
msgstr ""

#. type: Content of: <guide><chapter><section><body><p>
#: en/articles/lpi-101-administration-p2.xml:271
#, no-wrap
msgid ""
"It's important to note that the syntax inside square brackets is fundamentally\n"
"different from that in other parts of the regular expression. For example, if\n"
"you put a . inside square brackets, it allows the square brackets to match a\n"
"literal ., just like the 1 and 2 in the examples above. In comparison, a\n"
"literal . outside the square brackets is interpreted as a metacharacter unless\n"
"prefixed by a \\. We can take advantage of this fact to print a list of all\n"
"lines in <path>/etc/fstab</path> that contain the literal string dev.hda by\n"
"typing:\n"
msgstr ""

#. type: Attribute 'caption' of: <guide><chapter><section><body><pre>
#: en/articles/lpi-101-administration-p2.xml:281
#, no-wrap
msgid "Printing literals using brackets"
msgstr ""

#. type: Content of: <guide><chapter><section><body><pre>
#: en/articles/lpi-101-administration-p2.xml:282
#, no-wrap
msgid "$ <i>grep dev[.]hda /etc/fstab</i>\n"
msgstr ""

#. type: Content of: <guide><chapter><section><body><p>
#: en/articles/lpi-101-administration-p2.xml:286
#, no-wrap
msgid "Alternately, we could also type:\n"
msgstr ""

#. type: Attribute 'caption' of: <guide><chapter><section><body><pre>
#: en/articles/lpi-101-administration-p2.xml:289
#, no-wrap
msgid "Printing literals using escaping"
msgstr ""

#. type: Content of: <guide><chapter><section><body><pre>
#: en/articles/lpi-101-administration-p2.xml:290
#, no-wrap
msgid "$ <i>grep \"dev\\.hda\" /etc/fstab</i>\n"
msgstr ""

#. type: Content of: <guide><chapter><section><body><p>
#: en/articles/lpi-101-administration-p2.xml:294
#, no-wrap
msgid ""
"Neither regular expression is likely to match any lines in your\n"
"<path>/etc/fstab</path> file.\n"
msgstr ""

#. type: Content of: <guide><chapter><section><title>
#: en/articles/lpi-101-administration-p2.xml:301
#, no-wrap
msgid "The \"*\" metacharacter"
msgstr ""

#. type: Content of: <guide><chapter><section><body><p>
#: en/articles/lpi-101-administration-p2.xml:305
#, no-wrap
msgid ""
"Some metacharacters don't match anything in themselves, but instead modify the\n"
"meaning of a previous character. One such metacharacter is * (asterisk), which\n"
"is used to match zero or more repeated occurrences of the previous character.\n"
"Note that this means that the * has a different meaning in a regex than it does\n"
"with globs. Here are some examples, and play close attention to instances where\n"
"these regex matches differ from globs:\n"
msgstr ""

#. type: Content of: <guide><chapter><section><body><ul><li>
#: en/articles/lpi-101-administration-p2.xml:315
#, no-wrap
msgid ""
"    ab*c matches abbbbc but not abqc  (if a glob, it would match both strings\n"
"    -- can you figure out why?)\n"
"  "
msgstr ""

#. type: Content of: <guide><chapter><section><body><ul><li>
#: en/articles/lpi-101-administration-p2.xml:319
#, no-wrap
msgid ""
"    ab*c matches abc but not abbqbbc (again, if a glob, it would match both\n"
"    strings)\n"
"  "
msgstr ""

#. type: Content of: <guide><chapter><section><body><ul><li>
#: en/articles/lpi-101-administration-p2.xml:323
#, no-wrap
msgid ""
"    ab*c matches ac but not cba (if a glob, ac would not be matched, nor would\n"
"    cba)\n"
"  "
msgstr ""

#. type: Content of: <guide><chapter><section><body><ul><li>
#: en/articles/lpi-101-administration-p2.xml:327
#, no-wrap
msgid ""
"    b[cq]*e matches bqe and be (if a glob, it would match bqe but not be)\n"
"  "
msgstr ""

#. type: Content of: <guide><chapter><section><body><ul><li>
#: en/articles/lpi-101-administration-p2.xml:330
#, no-wrap
msgid ""
"    b[cq]*e matches bccqqe but not bccc (if a glob, it would match the first\n"
"    but not the second as well)\n"
"  "
msgstr ""

#. type: Content of: <guide><chapter><section><body><ul><li>
#: en/articles/lpi-101-administration-p2.xml:334
#, no-wrap
msgid ""
"    b[cq]*e matches bqqcce but not cqe (if a glob, it would match the first but\n"
"    not the second as well)\n"
"  "
msgstr ""

#. type: Content of: <guide><chapter><section><body><ul><li>
#: en/articles/lpi-101-administration-p2.xml:338
#, no-wrap
msgid ""
"    b[cq]*e matches bbbeee (this would not be the case with a glob)\n"
"  "
msgstr ""

#. type: Content of: <guide><chapter><section><body><ul><li>
#: en/articles/lpi-101-administration-p2.xml:341
#, no-wrap
msgid ""
"    .* will match any string. (if a glob, it would match any string starting\n"
"    with .)\n"
"  "
msgstr ""

#. type: Content of: <guide><chapter><section><body><ul><li>
#: en/articles/lpi-101-administration-p2.xml:345
#, no-wrap
msgid ""
"    foo.* will match any string that begins with foo (if a glob, it would match\n"
"    any string starting with the four literal characters foo..)\n"
"  "
msgstr ""

#. type: Content of: <guide><chapter><section><body><p>
#: en/articles/lpi-101-administration-p2.xml:351
#, no-wrap
msgid ""
"Now, for a quick brain-twisting review: the line ac matches the regex ab*c\n"
"because the asterisk also allows the preceding expression (b) to appear\n"
"<e>zero</e> times. Again, it's critical to note that the * regex metacharacter\n"
"is interpreted in a fundamentally different way than the * glob character.\n"
msgstr ""

#. type: Content of: <guide><chapter><section><title>
#: en/articles/lpi-101-administration-p2.xml:360
#, no-wrap
msgid "Beginning and end of line"
msgstr ""

#. type: Content of: <guide><chapter><section><body><p>
#: en/articles/lpi-101-administration-p2.xml:364
#, no-wrap
msgid ""
"The last metacharacters we will cover in detail here are the ^ and $\n"
"metacharacters, used to match the beginning and end of line, respectively. By\n"
"using a ^ at the beginning of your regex, you can cause your pattern to be\n"
"\"anchored\" to the start of the line. In the following example, we use the ^#\n"
"regex to match any line beginning with the # character:\n"
msgstr ""

#. type: Attribute 'caption' of: <guide><chapter><section><body><pre>
#: en/articles/lpi-101-administration-p2.xml:371
#, no-wrap
msgid "Lines"
msgstr ""

#. type: Content of: <guide><chapter><section><body><pre>
#: en/articles/lpi-101-administration-p2.xml:372
#, no-wrap
msgid ""
"$ <i>grep ^# /etc/fstab</i>\n"
"# /etc/fstab: static file system information.\n"
"#\n"
msgstr ""

#. type: Content of: <guide><chapter><section><title>
#: en/articles/lpi-101-administration-p2.xml:380
#, no-wrap
msgid "Full-line regexes"
msgstr ""

#. type: Content of: <guide><chapter><section><body><p>
#: en/articles/lpi-101-administration-p2.xml:384
#, no-wrap
msgid ""
"^ and $ can be combined to match an entire line. For example, the following\n"
"regex will match a line that starts with the # character and ends with the .\n"
"character, with any number of other characters in between:\n"
msgstr ""

#. type: Attribute 'caption' of: <guide><chapter><section><body><pre>
#: en/articles/lpi-101-administration-p2.xml:389
#, no-wrap
msgid "Matching an entire line"
msgstr ""

#. type: Content of: <guide><chapter><section><body><pre>
#: en/articles/lpi-101-administration-p2.xml:390
#, no-wrap
msgid ""
"$ <i>grep '^#.*\\.$' /etc/fstab</i>\n"
"# /etc/fstab: static file system information.\n"
msgstr ""

#. type: Content of: <guide><chapter><section><body><p>
#: en/articles/lpi-101-administration-p2.xml:395
#, no-wrap
msgid ""
"In the above example, we surrounded our regular expression with single quotes\n"
"to prevent $ from being interpreted by the shell. Without the single quotes,\n"
"the $ will disappear from our regex before grep even has a chance to take a\n"
"look at it.\n"
msgstr ""

#. type: Content of: <guide><chapter><title>
#: en/articles/lpi-101-administration-p2.xml:406
#, no-wrap
msgid "FHS and finding files"
msgstr ""

#. type: Content of: <guide><chapter><section><title>
#: en/articles/lpi-101-administration-p2.xml:408
#, no-wrap
msgid "Filesystem Hierarchy Standard"
msgstr ""

#. type: Content of: <guide><chapter><section><body><p>
#: en/articles/lpi-101-administration-p2.xml:412
#, no-wrap
msgid ""
"The Filesystem Hierarchy Standard is a document that specifies the layout of\n"
"directories on a Linux system. The FHS was devised to provide a common layout\n"
"to simplify distribution-independent software development -- so that stuff is\n"
"in generally the same place across Linux distributions. The FHS specifies the\n"
"following directory tree (taken directly from the FHS specification):\n"
msgstr ""

#. type: Content of: <guide><chapter><section><body><ul><li>
#: en/articles/lpi-101-administration-p2.xml:420
#, no-wrap
msgid "/ (the root directory)"
msgstr ""

#. type: Content of: <guide><chapter><section><body><ul><li>
#: en/articles/lpi-101-administration-p2.xml:421
#, no-wrap
msgid "/boot (static files of the boot loader)"
msgstr ""

#. type: Content of: <guide><chapter><section><body><ul><li>
#: en/articles/lpi-101-administration-p2.xml:422
#, no-wrap
msgid "/dev (device files)"
msgstr ""

#. type: Content of: <guide><chapter><section><body><ul><li>
#: en/articles/lpi-101-administration-p2.xml:423
#, no-wrap
msgid "/etc (host-specific system configuration)"
msgstr ""

#. type: Content of: <guide><chapter><section><body><ul><li>
#: en/articles/lpi-101-administration-p2.xml:424
#, no-wrap
