#. type: Content of: <guide><chapter><section><title>
#: en/articles/lpi-101-administration-p2.xml:436
#, no-wrap
msgid "The two independent FHS categories"
msgstr ""

#. type: Content of: <guide><chapter><section><body><p>
#: en/articles/lpi-101-administration-p2.xml:440
#, no-wrap
msgid ""
"The FHS bases its layout specification on the idea that there are two\n"
"independent categories of files: shareable vs. unshareable, and variable vs.\n"
"static. Shareable data can be shared between hosts; unshareable data is\n"
"specific to a given host (such as configuration files). Variable data can be\n"
"modified; static data is not modified (except at system installation and\n"
"maintenance).\n"
msgstr ""

#. type: Content of: <guide><chapter><section><body><p>
#: en/articles/lpi-101-administration-p2.xml:449
#, no-wrap
msgid ""
"The following grid summarizes the four possible combinations, with examples of\n"
"directories that would fall into those categories. Again, this table is\n"
"straight from the FHS specification:\n"
msgstr ""

#. type: Attribute 'caption' of: <guide><chapter><section><body><pre>
#: en/articles/lpi-101-administration-p2.xml:454
#, no-wrap
msgid "FHS"
msgstr ""

#. type: Content of: <guide><chapter><section><body><pre>
#: en/articles/lpi-101-administration-p2.xml:455
#, no-wrap
msgid ""
"+---------+-----------------+-------------+\n"
"|         | shareable       | unshareable |\n"
"+---------+-----------------+-------------+\n"
"|static   | /usr            | /etc        |\n"
"|         | /opt            | /boot       |\n"
"+---------+-----------------+-------------+\n"
"|variable | /var/mail       | /var/run    |\n"
"|         | /var/spool/news | /var/lock   |\n"
"+---------+-----------------+-------------+\n"
msgstr ""

#. type: Content of: <guide><chapter><section><title>
#: en/articles/lpi-101-administration-p2.xml:469
#, no-wrap
msgid "Secondary hierarchy at /usr"
msgstr ""

#. type: Content of: <guide><chapter><section><body><p>
#: en/articles/lpi-101-administration-p2.xml:473
#, no-wrap
msgid ""
"Under <path>/usr</path> you'll find a secondary hierarchy that looks a lot like\n"
"the root filesystem. It isn't critical for <path>/usr</path> to exist when the\n"
"machine powers up, so it can be shared on a network (shareable), or mounted\n"
"from a CD-ROM (static). Most Linux setups don't make use of sharing\n"
"<path>/usr</path>, but it's valuable to understand the usefulness of\n"
"distinguishing between the primary hierarchy at the root directory and the\n"
"secondary hierarchy at <path>/usr</path>.\n"
msgstr ""

#. type: Content of: <guide><chapter><section><body><p>
#: en/articles/lpi-101-administration-p2.xml:483
#, no-wrap
msgid ""
"This is all we'll say about the Filesystem Hierarchy Standard. The document\n"
"itself is quite readable, so you should go take a look at it. You'll understand\n"
"a lot more about the Linux filesystem if you read it. Find it at\n"
"<uri>http://www.pathname.com/fhs/</uri>.\n"
msgstr ""

#. type: Content of: <guide><chapter><section><title>
#: en/articles/lpi-101-administration-p2.xml:492
#, no-wrap
msgid "Finding files"
msgstr ""

#. type: Content of: <guide><chapter><section><body><p>
#: en/articles/lpi-101-administration-p2.xml:496
#, no-wrap
msgid ""
"Linux systems often contain hundreds of thousands of files. Perhaps you are\n"
"savvy enough to never lose track of any of them, but it's more likely that you\n"
"will occasionally need help finding one. There are a few different tools on\n"
"Linux for finding files. This introduction will help you choose the right tool\n"
"for the job.\n"
msgstr ""

#. type: Content of: <guide><chapter><section><title>
#: en/articles/lpi-101-administration-p2.xml:506
#, no-wrap
msgid "The PATH"
msgstr ""

#. type: Content of: <guide><chapter><section><body><p>
#: en/articles/lpi-101-administration-p2.xml:510
#, no-wrap
msgid ""
"When you run a program at the command line, bash actually searches through a\n"
"list of directories to find the program you requested. For example, when you\n"
"type <c>ls</c>, <c>bash</c> doesn't intrinsically know that the ls program\n"
"lives in <path>/usr/bin</path>. Instead, bash refers to an environment variable\n"
"called PATH, which is a colon-separated list of directories. We can examine the\n"
"value of PATH:\n"
msgstr ""

#. type: Attribute 'caption' of: <guide><chapter><section><body><pre>
#: en/articles/lpi-101-administration-p2.xml:518
#, no-wrap
msgid "Viewing your path"
msgstr ""

#. type: Content of: <guide><chapter><section><body><pre>
#: en/articles/lpi-101-administration-p2.xml:519
#, no-wrap
msgid ""
"$ <i>echo $PATH</i>\n"
"/usr/local/bin:/usr/bin:/bin:/usr/sbin:/sbin:/usr/X11R6/bin\n"
msgstr ""

#. type: Content of: <guide><chapter><section><body><p>
#: en/articles/lpi-101-administration-p2.xml:524
#, no-wrap
msgid ""
"Given this value of PATH (yours may differ,) bash would first check\n"
"<path>/usr/local/bin</path>, then <path>/usr/bin</path> for the <c>ls</c>\n"
"program. Most likely, <c>ls</c> is kept in <path>/usr/bin</path>, so bash would\n"
"stop at that point.\n"
msgstr ""

#. type: Content of: <guide><chapter><section><title>
#: en/articles/lpi-101-administration-p2.xml:533
#, no-wrap
msgid "Modifying PATH"
msgstr ""

#. type: Content of: <guide><chapter><section><body><p>
#: en/articles/lpi-101-administration-p2.xml:537
#, no-wrap
msgid "You can augment your PATH by assigning to it on the command line:\n"
msgstr ""

#. type: Attribute 'caption' of: <guide><chapter><section><body><pre>
#: en/articles/lpi-101-administration-p2.xml:540
#, no-wrap
msgid "Editing PATH"
msgstr ""

#. type: Content of: <guide><chapter><section><body><pre>
#: en/articles/lpi-101-administration-p2.xml:541
#, no-wrap
msgid ""
"$ <i>PATH=$PATH:~/bin</i>\n"
"$ <i>echo $PATH</i>\n"
"/usr/local/bin:/usr/bin:/bin:/usr/sbin:/sbin:/usr/X11R6/bin:/home/agriffis/bin\n"
msgstr ""

#. type: Content of: <guide><chapter><section><body><p>
#: en/articles/lpi-101-administration-p2.xml:547
#, no-wrap
msgid ""
"You can also remove elements from PATH, although it isn't as easy since you\n"
"can't refer to the existing $PATH. Your best bet is to simply type out the new\n"
"PATH you want:\n"
" "
msgstr ""

#. type: Attribute 'caption' of: <guide><chapter><section><body><pre>
#: en/articles/lpi-101-administration-p2.xml:552
#, no-wrap
msgid "Removing entries from PATH"
msgstr ""

#. type: Content of: <guide><chapter><section><body><pre>
#: en/articles/lpi-101-administration-p2.xml:553
#, no-wrap
msgid ""
"$ <i>PATH=/usr/local/bin:/usr/bin:/bin:/usr/X11R6/bin:~/bin</i>\n"
"$ <i>echo $PATH</i>\n"
"/usr/local/bin:/usr/bin:/bin:/usr/X11R6/bin:/home/agriffis/bin\n"
msgstr ""

#. type: Content of: <guide><chapter><section><body><p>
#: en/articles/lpi-101-administration-p2.xml:559
#, no-wrap
msgid ""
"To make your PATH changes available to any future processes you start from this\n"
"shell, export your changes using the export command:\n"
msgstr ""

#. type: Attribute 'caption' of: <guide><chapter><section><body><pre>
#: en/articles/lpi-101-administration-p2.xml:563
#, no-wrap
msgid "Exporting PATH (or any variable, for that matter)"
msgstr ""

#. type: Content of: <guide><chapter><section><body><pre>
#: en/articles/lpi-101-administration-p2.xml:564
#, no-wrap
msgid "$ <i>export PATH</i>\n"
msgstr ""

#. type: Content of: <guide><chapter><section><title>
#: en/articles/lpi-101-administration-p2.xml:570
#, no-wrap
msgid "All about \"which\""
msgstr ""

#. type: Content of: <guide><chapter><section><body><p>
#: en/articles/lpi-101-administration-p2.xml:574
#, no-wrap
msgid ""
"You can check to see if there's a given program in your PATH by using\n"
"<c>which</c>. For example, here we find out that our Linux system has no\n"
"(common) sense:\n"
msgstr ""

#. type: Attribute 'caption' of: <guide><chapter><section><body><pre>
#: en/articles/lpi-101-administration-p2.xml:579
#, no-wrap
msgid "Looking for sense"
msgstr ""

#. type: Content of: <guide><chapter><section><body><pre>
#: en/articles/lpi-101-administration-p2.xml:580
#, no-wrap
msgid ""
"$ which <i>sense</i>\n"
"which: no sense in (/usr/local/bin:/usr/bin:/bin:/usr/sbin:/sbin:/usr/X11R6/bin)\n"
msgstr ""

#. type: Content of: <guide><chapter><section><body><p>
#: en/articles/lpi-101-administration-p2.xml:585
#, no-wrap
msgid "In this example, we successfully locate <c>ls</c>:\n"
msgstr ""

#. type: Attribute 'caption' of: <guide><chapter><section><body><pre>
#: en/articles/lpi-101-administration-p2.xml:588
#, no-wrap
msgid "Looking for ls"
msgstr ""

#. type: Content of: <guide><chapter><section><body><pre>
#: en/articles/lpi-101-administration-p2.xml:589
#, no-wrap
msgid ""
"$ <i>which ls</i>\n"
"/usr/bin/ls\n"
msgstr ""

#. type: Content of: <guide><chapter><section><title>
#: en/articles/lpi-101-administration-p2.xml:596
#, no-wrap
msgid "\"which -a\""
msgstr ""

#. type: Content of: <guide><chapter><section><body><p>
#: en/articles/lpi-101-administration-p2.xml:600
#, no-wrap
msgid ""
"Finally, you should be aware of the <c>-a</c> flag, which causes <c>which</c>\n"
"to show you all of the instances of a given program in your PATH:\n"
msgstr ""

#. type: Attribute 'caption' of: <guide><chapter><section><body><pre>
#: en/articles/lpi-101-administration-p2.xml:604
#, no-wrap
msgid "Finding all instances of a program in your PATH"
msgstr ""

#. type: Content of: <guide><chapter><section><body><pre>
#: en/articles/lpi-101-administration-p2.xml:605
#, no-wrap
msgid ""
"$ <i>which -a ls</i>\n"
"/usr/bin/ls\n"
"/bin/ls\n"
msgstr ""

#. type: Content of: <guide><chapter><section><title>
#: en/articles/lpi-101-administration-p2.xml:613
#, no-wrap
msgid "whereis"
msgstr ""

#. type: Content of: <guide><chapter><section><body><p>
#: en/articles/lpi-101-administration-p2.xml:617
#, no-wrap
msgid ""
"If you're interested in finding more information than purely the location of a\n"
"program, you might try the <c>whereis</c> program:\n"
msgstr ""

#. type: Attribute 'caption' of: <guide><chapter><section><body><pre>
#: en/articles/lpi-101-administration-p2.xml:621
#, no-wrap
msgid "Using whereis"
msgstr ""

#. type: Content of: <guide><chapter><section><body><pre>
#: en/articles/lpi-101-administration-p2.xml:622
#, no-wrap
msgid ""
"$ <i>whereis ls</i>\n"
"ls: /bin/ls /usr/bin/ls /usr/share/man/man1/ls.1.gz\n"
msgstr ""

#. type: Content of: <guide><chapter><section><body><p>
#: en/articles/lpi-101-administration-p2.xml:627
#, no-wrap
msgid ""
"Here we see that <c>ls</c> occurs in two common binary locations,\n"
"<path>/bin</path> and <path>/usr/bin</path>. Additionally, we are informed that\n"
"there is a manual page located in <path>/usr/share/man</path>. This is the\n"
"man-page you would see if you were to type <c>man ls</c>.\n"
msgstr ""

#. type: Content of: <guide><chapter><section><body><p>
#: en/articles/lpi-101-administration-p2.xml:634
#, no-wrap
msgid ""
"The <c>whereis</c> program also has the ability to search for sources, to\n"
"specify alternate search paths, and to search for unusual entries. Refer to the\n"
"whereis man-page for further information.\n"
msgstr ""

#. type: Content of: <guide><chapter><section><title>
#: en/articles/lpi-101-administration-p2.xml:642
#, no-wrap
msgid "find"
msgstr ""

#. type: Content of: <guide><chapter><section><body><p>
#: en/articles/lpi-101-administration-p2.xml:646
#, no-wrap
msgid ""
"The <c>find</c> command is another handy tool for your toolbox. With find you\n"
"aren't restricted to programs; you can search for any file you want, using a\n"
"variety of search criteria. For example, to search for a file by the name of\n"
"README, starting in <path>/usr/share/doc</path>:\n"
msgstr ""

#. type: Attribute 'caption' of: <guide><chapter><section><body><pre>
#: en/articles/lpi-101-administration-p2.xml:652
#, no-wrap
msgid "Using find"
msgstr ""

#. type: Content of: <guide><chapter><section><body><pre>
#: en/articles/lpi-101-administration-p2.xml:653
#, no-wrap
msgid ""
"$ <i>find /usr/share/doc -name README</i>\n"
"/usr/share/doc/ion-20010523/README\n"
"/usr/share/doc/bind-9.1.3-r6/dhcp-dynamic-dns-examples/README\n"
"/usr/share/doc/sane-1.0.5/README\n"
msgstr ""

#. type: Content of: <guide><chapter><section><title>
#: en/articles/lpi-101-administration-p2.xml:662
#, no-wrap
msgid "find and wildcards"
msgstr ""

#. type: Content of: <guide><chapter><section><body><p>
#: en/articles/lpi-101-administration-p2.xml:666
#, no-wrap
msgid ""
"You can use \"glob\" wildcards in the argument to -name, provided that you quote\n"
"them or backslash-escape them (so they get passed to find intact rather than\n"
"being expanded by bash). For example, we might want to search for README files\n"
"with extensions:\n"
msgstr ""

#. type: Attribute 'caption' of: <guide><chapter><section><body><pre>
#: en/articles/lpi-101-administration-p2.xml:672
#, no-wrap
msgid "Using find with wildcards"
msgstr ""

#. type: Content of: <guide><chapter><section><body><pre>
#: en/articles/lpi-101-administration-p2.xml:673
#, no-wrap
msgid ""
"$ <i>find /usr/share/doc -name README\\*</i>\n"
"/usr/share/doc/iproute2-2.4.7/README.gz\n"
"/usr/share/doc/iproute2-2.4.7/README.iproute2+tc.gz\n"
"/usr/share/doc/iproute2-2.4.7/README.decnet.gz\n"
"/usr/share/doc/iproute2-2.4.7/examples/diffserv/README.gz\n"
"/usr/share/doc/pilot-link-0.9.6-r2/README.gz\n"
"/usr/share/doc/gnome-pilot-conduits-0.8/README.gz\n"
"/usr/share/doc/gimp-1.2.2/README.i18n.gz\n"
"/usr/share/doc/gimp-1.2.2/README.win32.gz\n"
"/usr/share/doc/gimp-1.2.2/README.gz\n"
"/usr/share/doc/gimp-1.2.2/README.perl.gz\n"
"[578 additional lines snipped]\n"
msgstr ""

#. type: Attribute 'caption' of: <guide><chapter><section><body><pre>
#: en/articles/lpi-101-administration-p2.xml:690
#: en/articles/lpi-101-administration-p2.xml:697
#, no-wrap
msgid "Ignoring case with find"
msgstr ""

#. type: Content of: <guide><chapter><section><body><p>
#: en/articles/lpi-101-administration-p2.xml:694
#, no-wrap
msgid "Of course, you might want to ignore case in your search:\n"
msgstr ""

#. type: Content of: <guide><chapter><section><body><pre>
#: en/articles/lpi-101-administration-p2.xml:698
#, no-wrap
msgid "$ <i>find /usr/share/doc -name '[Rr][Ee][Aa][Dd][Mm][Ee]*'</i>\n"
msgstr ""

#. type: Content of: <guide><chapter><section><body><p>
#: en/articles/lpi-101-administration-p2.xml:702
#, no-wrap
msgid "Or, more simply:\n"
msgstr ""

#. type: Attribute 'caption' of: <guide><chapter><section><body><pre>
#: en/articles/lpi-101-administration-p2.xml:705
#, no-wrap
msgid "Another method"
msgstr ""

#. type: Content of: <guide><chapter><section><body><pre>
#: en/articles/lpi-101-administration-p2.xml:706
#, no-wrap
msgid "$ <i>find /usr/share/doc -iname readme\\*</i>\n"
msgstr ""

#. type: Content of: <guide><chapter><section><body><p>
#: en/articles/lpi-101-administration-p2.xml:710
#, no-wrap
msgid "As you can see, you can use <c>-iname</c> to do case-insensitive searching.\n"
msgstr ""

#. type: Content of: <guide><chapter><section><title>
#: en/articles/lpi-101-administration-p2.xml:716
#, no-wrap
msgid "find and regular expressions"
msgstr ""

#. type: Content of: <guide><chapter><section><body><p>
#: en/articles/lpi-101-administration-p2.xml:720
#, no-wrap
msgid ""
"If you're familiar with regular expressions, you can use the <c>-regex</c>\n"
"option to limit the output to filenames that match a pattern. And similar to\n"
"the <c>-iname</c> option, there is a corresponding <c>-iregex</c> option that\n"
"ignores case in the pattern. For example:\n"
msgstr ""

#. type: Attribute 'caption' of: <guide><chapter><section><body><pre>
#: en/articles/lpi-101-administration-p2.xml:726
#, no-wrap
msgid "Regex and find"
msgstr ""

#. type: Content of: <guide><chapter><section><body><pre>
#: en/articles/lpi-101-administration-p2.xml:727
#, no-wrap
msgid ""
"$ <i>find /etc -iregex '.*xt.*'</i>\n"
"/etc/X11/xkb/types/extra\n"
"/etc/X11/xkb/semantics/xtest\n"
"/etc/X11/xkb/compat/xtest\n"
"/etc/X11/app-defaults/XTerm\n"
"/etc/X11/app-defaults/XTerm-color\n"
msgstr ""

#. type: Content of: <guide><chapter><section><body><p>
#: en/articles/lpi-101-administration-p2.xml:736
#, no-wrap
msgid ""
"Note that unlike many programs, <c>find</c> requires that the regex specified\n"
"matches the entire path, not just a part of it. For that reason, specifying the\n"
"leading and trailing .* is necessary; purely using xt as the regex would not be\n"
"sufficient.\n"
msgstr ""

#. type: Content of: <guide><chapter><section><title>
#: en/articles/lpi-101-administration-p2.xml:745
#, no-wrap
msgid "find and types"
msgstr ""

#. type: Content of: <guide><chapter><section><body><p>
#: en/articles/lpi-101-administration-p2.xml:749
#, no-wrap
msgid ""
"The <c>-type</c> option allows you to find filesystem objects of a certain\n"
"type. The possible arguments to -type are <c>b</c> (block device), <c>c</c>\n"
"(character device), <c>d</c> (directory), <c>p</c> (named pipe), <c>f</c>\n"
"(regular file), <c>l</c> (symbolic link), and <c>s</c> (socket). For example,\n"
"to search for symbolic links in <path>/usr/bin</path> that contain the string\n"
"vim:\n"
msgstr ""

#. type: Attribute 'caption' of: <guide><chapter><section><body><pre>
#: en/articles/lpi-101-administration-p2.xml:757
#, no-wrap
msgid "Restricting find by type"
msgstr ""

#. type: Content of: <guide><chapter><section><body><pre>
#: en/articles/lpi-101-administration-p2.xml:758
#, no-wrap
msgid ""
"$ <i>find /usr/bin -name '*vim*' -type l</i>\n"
"/usr/bin/rvim\n"
"/usr/bin/vimdiff\n"
"/usr/bin/gvimdiff\n"
msgstr ""

#. type: Content of: <guide><chapter><section><title>
#: en/articles/lpi-101-administration-p2.xml:767
#, no-wrap
msgid "find and mtimes"
msgstr ""

#. type: Content of: <guide><chapter><section><body><p>
#: en/articles/lpi-101-administration-p2.xml:771
#, no-wrap
msgid ""
"The <c>-mtime</c> option allows you to select files based on their last\n"
"modification time. The argument to mtime is in terms of 24-hour periods, and is\n"
"most useful when entered with either a plus sign (meaning \"after\") or a minus\n"
"sign (meaning \"before\"). For example, consider the following scenario:\n"
msgstr ""

#. type: Attribute 'caption' of: <guide><chapter><section><body><pre>
#: en/articles/lpi-101-administration-p2.xml:777
#, no-wrap
msgid "Scenario"
msgstr ""

#. type: Content of: <guide><chapter><section><body><pre>
#: en/articles/lpi-101-administration-p2.xml:778
#, no-wrap
msgid ""
"$ <i>ls -l ?</i>\n"
"-rw-------    1 root     root            0 Jan  7 18:00 a\n"
"-rw-------    1 root     root            0 Jan  6 18:00 b\n"
"-rw-------    1 root     root            0 Jan  5 18:00 c\n"
"-rw-------    1 root     root            0 Jan  4 18:00 d\n"
"$ <i>date</i>\n"
"Mon May  7 18:14:52 EST 2003\n"
msgstr ""

#. type: Content of: <guide><chapter><section><body><p>
#: en/articles/lpi-101-administration-p2.xml:788
#, no-wrap
msgid "You could search for files that were created in the past 24 hours:\n"
msgstr ""

#. type: Attribute 'caption' of: <guide><chapter><section><body><pre>
#: en/articles/lpi-101-administration-p2.xml:791
#, no-wrap
msgid "Files created in the last 24 hours"
msgstr ""

#. type: Content of: <guide><chapter><section><body><pre>
#: en/articles/lpi-101-administration-p2.xml:792
#, no-wrap
msgid ""
"$ <i>find . -name \\? -mtime -1</i>\n"
"./a\n"
msgstr ""

#. type: Content of: <guide><chapter><section><body><p>
#: en/articles/lpi-101-administration-p2.xml:797
#, no-wrap
msgid ""
"Or you could search for files that were created prior to the current 24-hour\n"
"period:\n"
msgstr ""

#. type: Attribute 'caption' of: <guide><chapter><section><body><pre>
#: en/articles/lpi-101-administration-p2.xml:801
#, no-wrap
msgid "Files created before the last 24 hours"
msgstr ""

#. type: Content of: <guide><chapter><section><body><pre>
#: en/articles/lpi-101-administration-p2.xml:802
#, no-wrap
msgid ""
"$ <i>find . -name \\? -mtime +0</i>\n"
"./b\n"
"./c\n"
"./d\n"
msgstr ""

#. type: Content of: <guide><chapter><section><title>
#: en/articles/lpi-101-administration-p2.xml:811
#, no-wrap
msgid "The -daystart option"
msgstr ""

#. type: Content of: <guide><chapter><section><body><p>
#: en/articles/lpi-101-administration-p2.xml:815
#, no-wrap
msgid ""
"If you additionally specify the <c>-daystart</c> option, then the periods of\n"
"time start at the beginning of today rather than 24 hours ago. For example,\n"
"here is a set of files created yesterday and the day before:\n"
msgstr ""

#. type: Attribute 'caption' of: <guide><chapter><section><body><pre>
#: en/articles/lpi-101-administration-p2.xml:820
#, no-wrap
msgid "Using -daystart"
msgstr ""

#. type: Content of: <guide><chapter><section><body><pre>
#: en/articles/lpi-101-administration-p2.xml:821
#, no-wrap
msgid ""
"$ <i>find . -name \\? -daystart -mtime +0 -mtime -3</i>\n"
"./b\n"
"./c\n"
"$ ls -l b c\n"
"-rw-------    1 root     root            0 May  6 18:00 b\n"
"-rw-------    1 root     root            0 May  5 18:00 c\n"
msgstr ""

#. type: Content of: <guide><chapter><section><title>
#: en/articles/lpi-101-administration-p2.xml:832
#, no-wrap
msgid "The -size option"
msgstr ""

#. type: Content of: <guide><chapter><section><body><p>
#: en/articles/lpi-101-administration-p2.xml:836
#, no-wrap
msgid ""
"The <c>-size</c> option allows you to find files based on their size. By\n"
"default, the argument to <c>-size</c> is 512-byte blocks, but adding a suffix\n"
"can make things easier. The available suffixes are <c>b</c> (512-byte blocks),\n"
"<c>c</c> (bytes), <c>k</c> (kilobytes), and <c>w</c> (2-byte words).\n"
"Additionally, you can prepend a plus sign (\"larger than\") or minus sign\n"
"(\"smaller than\").\n"
msgstr ""

#. type: Content of: <guide><chapter><section><body><p>
#: en/articles/lpi-101-administration-p2.xml:845
#, no-wrap
msgid ""
"For example, to find regular files in <path>/usr/bin</path> that are smaller\n"
"than 50 bytes:\n"
msgstr ""

#. type: Attribute 'caption' of: <guide><chapter><section><body><pre>
#: en/articles/lpi-101-administration-p2.xml:849
#, no-wrap
msgid "-size in action"
msgstr ""

#. type: Content of: <guide><chapter><section><body><pre>
#: en/articles/lpi-101-administration-p2.xml:850
#, no-wrap
msgid ""
"$ <i>find /usr/bin -type f -size -50c</i>\n"
"/usr/bin/krdb\n"
"/usr/bin/run-nautilus\n"
"/usr/bin/sgmlwhich\n"
"/usr/bin/muttbug\n"
msgstr ""

#. type: Content of: <guide><chapter><section><title>
#: en/articles/lpi-101-administration-p2.xml:860
#, no-wrap
msgid "Processing found files"
msgstr ""

#. type: Content of: <guide><chapter><section><body><p>
#: en/articles/lpi-101-administration-p2.xml:864
#, no-wrap
msgid ""
"You may be wondering what you can do with all these files that you find! Well,\n"
"<c>find</c> has the ability to act on the files that it finds by using the\n"
"<c>-exec</c> option. This option accepts a command line to execute as its\n"
"argument, terminated with ;, and it replaces any occurrences of {} with the\n"
"filename. This is best understood with an example:\n"
msgstr ""

#. type: Attribute 'caption' of: <guide><chapter><section><body><pre>
#: en/articles/lpi-101-administration-p2.xml:871
#, no-wrap
msgid "Using -exec"
msgstr ""

#. type: Content of: <guide><chapter><section><body><pre>
#: en/articles/lpi-101-administration-p2.xml:872
#, no-wrap
msgid ""
"$ <i>find /usr/bin -type f -size -50c -exec ls -l '{}' ';'</i>\n"
"-rwxr-xr-x    1 root     root           27 Oct 28 07:13 /usr/bin/krdb\n"
"-rwxr-xr-x    1 root     root           35 Nov 28 18:26 /usr/bin/run-nautilus\n"
"-rwxr-xr-x    1 root     root           25 Oct 21 17:51 /usr/bin/sgmlwhich\n"
"-rwxr-xr-x    1 root     root           26 Sep 26 08:00 /usr/bin/muttbug\n"
msgstr ""

#. type: Content of: <guide><chapter><section><body><p>
#: en/articles/lpi-101-administration-p2.xml:880
#, no-wrap
msgid ""
"As you can see, <c>find</c> is a very powerful command. It has grown through\n"
"the years of UNIX and Linux development. There are many other useful options to\n"
"find. You can learn about them in the find manual page.\n"
msgstr ""

#. type: Content of: <guide><chapter><section><title>
#: en/articles/lpi-101-administration-p2.xml:888
#, no-wrap
msgid "locate"
msgstr ""

#. type: Content of: <guide><chapter><section><body><p>
#: en/articles/lpi-101-administration-p2.xml:892
#, no-wrap
msgid ""
"We have covered <c>which</c>, <c>whereis</c>, and <c>find</c>. You might have\n"
"noticed that <c>find</c> can take a while to execute, since it needs to read\n"
"each directory that it's searching. It turns out that the <c>locate</c> command\n"
"can speed things up by relying on an external database generated by\n"
"<c>updatedb</c> (which we'll cover in the next panel.)\n"
msgstr ""

#. type: Content of: <guide><chapter><section><body><p>
#: en/articles/lpi-101-administration-p2.xml:900
#, no-wrap
msgid ""
"The <c>locate</c> command matches against any part of a pathname, not just the\n"
"file itself. For example:\n"
msgstr ""

#. type: Attribute 'caption' of: <guide><chapter><section><body><pre>
#: en/articles/lpi-101-administration-p2.xml:904
#, no-wrap
msgid "locate in action"
msgstr ""

#. type: Content of: <guide><chapter><section><body><pre>
#: en/articles/lpi-101-administration-p2.xml:905
#, no-wrap
msgid ""
"$ <i>locate bin/ls</i>\n"
"/var/ftp/bin/ls\n"
"/bin/ls\n"
"/sbin/lsmod\n"
"/sbin/lspci\n"
"/usr/bin/lsattr\n"
"/usr/bin/lspgpot\n"
"/usr/sbin/lsof\n"
msgstr ""

#. type: Content of: <guide><chapter><section><title>
#: en/articles/lpi-101-administration-p2.xml:918
#, no-wrap
msgid "Using updatedb"
msgstr ""

#. type: Content of: <guide><chapter><section><body><p>
#: en/articles/lpi-101-administration-p2.xml:922
#, no-wrap
msgid ""
"Most Linux systems have a \"cron job\" to update the database periodically. If\n"
"your <c>locate</c> returned an error such as the following, then you will need\n"
"to run <c>updatedb</c> as root to generate the search database:\n"
msgstr ""

#. type: Attribute 'caption' of: <guide><chapter><section><body><pre>
#: en/articles/lpi-101-administration-p2.xml:927
#, no-wrap
msgid "updating your locate database"
msgstr ""

#. type: Content of: <guide><chapter><section><body><pre>
#: en/articles/lpi-101-administration-p2.xml:928
#, no-wrap
msgid ""
"$ <i>locate bin/ls</i>\n"
"locate: /var/spool/locate/locatedb: No such file or directory\n"
"$ <i>su -</i>\n"
"Password:\n"
"# <i>updatedb</i>\n"
msgstr ""

#. type: Content of: <guide><chapter><section><body><p>
#: en/articles/lpi-101-administration-p2.xml:936
#, no-wrap
msgid ""
"The <c>updatedb</c> command may take a long time to run. If you have a noisy\n"
"hard disk, you will hear a lot of racket as the entire filesystem is indexed.\n"
":)\n"
msgstr ""

#. type: Content of: <guide><chapter><section><title>
#: en/articles/lpi-101-administration-p2.xml:945
#, no-wrap
msgid "mlocate"
msgstr ""

#. type: Content of: <guide><chapter><section><body><p>
#: en/articles/lpi-101-administration-p2.xml:949
#, no-wrap
msgid ""
"On many Linux distributions, the <c>locate</c> command has been replaced by\n"
"<c>mlocate</c>. There is typically a symbolic link to <c>locate</c>, so that\n"
"you don't need to remember which you have. <c>mlocate</c> stands for \"secure\n"
"locate.\" It stores permissions information in the database so that normal users\n"
"can't pry into directories they would otherwise be unable to read. The usage\n"
"information for <c>mlocate</c> is essentially the same as for <c>locate</c>,\n"
"although the output might be different depending on the user running the\n"
"command.\n"
msgstr ""

#. type: Content of: <guide><chapter><title>
#: en/articles/lpi-101-administration-p2.xml:963
#, no-wrap
msgid "Process Control"
msgstr ""

#. type: Content of: <guide><chapter><section><title>
#: en/articles/lpi-101-administration-p2.xml:965
#, no-wrap
msgid "Staring xeyes"
msgstr ""

#. type: Content of: <guide><chapter><section><body><p>
#: en/articles/lpi-101-administration-p2.xml:969
#, no-wrap
msgid ""
"To learn about process control, we first need to start a process. Make sure\n"
"that you have X running and execute the following command:\n"
msgstr ""

#. type: Attribute 'caption' of: <guide><chapter><section><body><pre>
#: en/articles/lpi-101-administration-p2.xml:973
#, no-wrap
msgid "Starting a Process"
msgstr ""

#. type: Content of: <guide><chapter><section><body><pre>
#: en/articles/lpi-101-administration-p2.xml:974
#, no-wrap
msgid "$ <i>xeyes -center red</i>\n"
msgstr ""

#. type: Content of: <guide><chapter><section><body><p>
#: en/articles/lpi-101-administration-p2.xml:978
#, no-wrap
msgid ""
"You will notice that an xeyes window pops up, and the red eyeballs follow your\n"
"mouse around the screen. You may also notice that you don't have a new prompt\n"
"in your terminal.\n"
msgstr ""

#. type: Content of: <guide><chapter><section><title>
#: en/articles/lpi-101-administration-p2.xml:986
#, no-wrap
msgid "Stopping a process"
msgstr ""

#. type: Content of: <guide><chapter><section><body><p>
#: en/articles/lpi-101-administration-p2.xml:990
#, no-wrap
msgid "To get a prompt back, you could type Control-C (often written as Ctrl-C or ^C):\n"
msgstr ""

#. type: Content of: <guide><chapter><section><body><p>
#: en/articles/lpi-101-administration-p2.xml:994
#, no-wrap
msgid ""
"You get a new bash prompt, but the xeyes window disappeared. In fact, the\n"
"entire process has been killed. Instead of killing it with Control-C, we could\n"
"have just stopped it with Control-Z:\n"
msgstr ""

#. type: Attribute 'caption' of: <guide><chapter><section><body><pre>
#: en/articles/lpi-101-administration-p2.xml:999
#, no-wrap
msgid "Stopping a Process"
msgstr ""

#. type: Content of: <guide><chapter><section><body><pre>
#: en/articles/lpi-101-administration-p2.xml:1000
#, no-wrap
msgid ""
"$ <i>xeyes -center red</i>\n"
"<i>Control-Z</i>\n"
"[1]+  Stopped                 xeyes -center red\n"
"$\n"
msgstr ""

#. type: Content of: <guide><chapter><section><body><p>
#: en/articles/lpi-101-administration-p2.xml:1007
#, no-wrap
msgid ""
"This time you get a new bash prompt, and the xeyes windows stays up. If you\n"
"play with it a bit, however, you will notice that the eyeballs are frozen in\n"
"place. If the xeyes window gets covered by another window and then uncovered\n"
"again, you will see that it doesn't even redraw the eyes at all. The process\n"
"isn't doing anything. It is, in fact, \"Stopped.\"\n"
msgstr ""

#. type: Content of: <guide><chapter><section><title>
#: en/articles/lpi-101-administration-p2.xml:1017
#, no-wrap
msgid "fg and bg"
msgstr ""

#. type: Content of: <guide><chapter><section><body><p>
#: en/articles/lpi-101-administration-p2.xml:1021
#, no-wrap
msgid ""
"To get the process \"un-stopped\" and running again, we can bring it to the\n"
"foreground with the bash built-in <c>fg</c>:\n"
msgstr ""

#. type: Attribute 'caption' of: <guide><chapter><section><body><pre>
#: en/articles/lpi-101-administration-p2.xml:1025
#, no-wrap
msgid "using fg"
msgstr ""

#. type: Content of: <guide><chapter><section><body><pre>
#: en/articles/lpi-101-administration-p2.xml:1026
#, no-wrap
msgid ""
"$ <i>fg</i>\n"
"<comment>(test it out, then stop the process again)</comment>\n"
"<i>Control-Z</i>\n"
"[1]+  Stopped                 xeyes -center red\n"
"$\n"
msgstr ""

#. type: Content of: <guide><chapter><section><body><p>
#: en/articles/lpi-101-administration-p2.xml:1034
#, no-wrap
msgid "Now continue it in the background with the bash built-in <c>bg</c>:\n"
msgstr ""

#. type: Attribute 'caption' of: <guide><chapter><section><body><pre>
#: en/articles/lpi-101-administration-p2.xml:1037
#, no-wrap
msgid "using bg"
msgstr ""

#. type: Content of: <guide><chapter><section><body><pre>
#: en/articles/lpi-101-administration-p2.xml:1038
#, no-wrap
msgid ""
"$ <i>bg</i>\n"
"[1]+ xeyes -center red &amp;\n"
"$\n"
msgstr ""

#. type: Content of: <guide><chapter><section><body><p>
#: en/articles/lpi-101-administration-p2.xml:1044
#, no-wrap
msgid ""
"Great! The xeyes process is now running in the background, and we have a new,\n"
"working bash prompt.\n"
msgstr ""

#. type: Content of: <guide><chapter><section><title>
#: en/articles/lpi-101-administration-p2.xml:1051
#, no-wrap
msgid "Using \"&amp;\""
msgstr ""

#. type: Content of: <guide><chapter><section><body><p>
#: en/articles/lpi-101-administration-p2.xml:1055
#, no-wrap
msgid ""
"If we wanted to start xeyes in the background from the beginning (instead of\n"
"using Control-Z and bg), we could have just added an \"&amp;\" (ampersand) to the\n"
"end of xeyes command line:\n"
msgstr ""

#. type: Attribute 'caption' of: <guide><chapter><section><body><pre>
#: en/articles/lpi-101-administration-p2.xml:1060
#, no-wrap
msgid "Using ampersands to background processes"
msgstr ""

#. type: Content of: <guide><chapter><section><body><pre>
#: en/articles/lpi-101-administration-p2.xml:1061
#, no-wrap
msgid ""
"$ <i>xeyes -center blue &amp;</i>\n"
"[2] 16224\n"
msgstr ""

#. type: Content of: <guide><chapter><section><title>
#: en/articles/lpi-101-administration-p2.xml:1068
#, no-wrap
msgid "Multiple background processes"
msgstr ""

#. type: Content of: <guide><chapter><section><body><p>
#: en/articles/lpi-101-administration-p2.xml:1072
#, no-wrap
msgid ""
"Now we have both a red and a blue xeyes running in the background. We can list\n"
"these jobs with the bash built-in <c>jobs</c>:\n"
msgstr ""

#. type: Attribute 'caption' of: <guide><chapter><section><body><pre>
#: en/articles/lpi-101-administration-p2.xml:1076
#, no-wrap
msgid "Using jobs"
msgstr ""

#. type: Content of: <guide><chapter><section><body><pre>
#: en/articles/lpi-101-administration-p2.xml:1077
#, no-wrap
msgid ""
"$ <i>jobs -l</i>\n"
"[1]- 16217 Running                 xeyes -center red &amp;\n"
"[2]+ 16224 Running                 xeyes -center blue &amp;\n"
msgstr ""

#. type: Content of: <guide><chapter><section><body><p>
#: en/articles/lpi-101-administration-p2.xml:1083
#, no-wrap
msgid ""
"The numbers in the left column are the job numbers bash assigned when they were\n"
"started. Job 2 has a + (plus) to indicate that it's the \"current job,\" which\n"
"means that typing <c>fg</c> will bring it to the foreground. You could also\n"
"foreground a specific job by specifying its number; for example, <c>fg 1</c>\n"
"would make the red xeyes the foreground task. The next column is the process id\n"
"or pid, included in the listing courtesy of the -l option to jobs. Finally,\n"
"both jobs are currently \"Running,\" and their command lines are listed to the\n"
"right.\n"
msgstr ""

#. type: Content of: <guide><chapter><section><title>
#: en/articles/lpi-101-administration-p2.xml:1096
#, no-wrap
msgid "Introducing signals"
msgstr ""

#. type: Content of: <guide><chapter><section><body><p>
#: en/articles/lpi-101-administration-p2.xml:1100
#, no-wrap
msgid ""
"To kill, stop, or continue processes, Linux uses a special form of\n"
"communication called \"signals.\" By sending a certain signal to a process, you\n"
"can get it to terminate, stop, or do other things. This is what you're actually\n"
"doing when you type Control-C, Control-Z, or use the <c>bg</c> or <c>fg</c>\n"
"built-ins -- you're using bash to send a particular signal to the process.\n"
"These signals can also be sent using the <c>kill</c> command and specifying the\n"
"pid (process id) on the command line:\n"
msgstr ""

#. type: Attribute 'caption' of: <guide><chapter><section><body><pre>
#: en/articles/lpi-101-administration-p2.xml:1109
#, no-wrap
msgid "Using kill"
msgstr ""

#. type: Content of: <guide><chapter><section><body><pre>
#: en/articles/lpi-101-administration-p2.xml:1110
#, no-wrap
msgid ""
"$ <i>kill -s SIGSTOP 16224</i>\n"
"$ <i>jobs -l</i>\n"
"[1]- 16217 Running                 xeyes -center red &amp;\n"
"[2]+ 16224 Stopped (signal)        xeyes -center blue\n"
msgstr ""

#. type: Content of: <guide><chapter><section><body><p>
#: en/articles/lpi-101-administration-p2.xml:1117
#, no-wrap
msgid ""
"As you can see, kill doesn't necessarily \"kill\" a process, although it can.\n"
"Using the \"-s\" option, <c>kill</c> can send any signal to a process. Linux\n"
"kills, stops or continues processes when they are sent the SIGINT, SIGSTOP, or\n"
"SIGCONT signals respectively. There are also other signals that you can send to\n"
"a process; some of these signals may be interpreted in an application-dependent\n"
"way. You can learn what signals a particular process recognizes by looking at\n"
"its man-page and searching for a SIGNALS section.\n"
msgstr ""

#. type: Content of: <guide><chapter><section><title>
#: en/articles/lpi-101-administration-p2.xml:1129
#, no-wrap
msgid "SIGTERM and SIGINT"
msgstr ""

#. type: Content of: <guide><chapter><section><body><p>
#: en/articles/lpi-101-administration-p2.xml:1133
#, no-wrap
msgid ""
"If you want to kill a process, you have several options. By default, kill sends\n"
"SIGTERM, which is not identical to SIGINT of Control-C fame, but usually has\n"
"the same results:\n"
msgstr ""

#. type: Attribute 'caption' of: <guide><chapter><section><body><pre>
#: en/articles/lpi-101-administration-p2.xml:1138
#, no-wrap
msgid "Using kill to terminate a process"
msgstr ""

#. type: Content of: <guide><chapter><section><body><pre>
#: en/articles/lpi-101-administration-p2.xml:1139
#, no-wrap
msgid ""
"$ <i>kill 16217</i>\n"
"$ <i>jobs -l</i>\n"
"[1]- 16217 Terminated              xeyes -center red\n"
"[2]+ 16224 Stopped (signal)        xeyes -center blue\n"
msgstr ""

#. type: Content of: <guide><chapter><section><title>
#: en/articles/lpi-101-administration-p2.xml:1148
#, no-wrap
msgid "The big kill"
msgstr ""

#. type: Content of: <guide><chapter><section><body><p>
#: en/articles/lpi-101-administration-p2.xml:1152
#, no-wrap
msgid ""
"Processes can ignore both SIGTERM and SIGINT, either by choice or because they\n"
"are stopped or somehow \"stuck.\" In these cases it may be necessary to use the\n"
"big hammer, the SIGKILL signal. A process cannot ignore SIGKILL:\n"
msgstr ""

#. type: Attribute 'caption' of: <guide><chapter><section><body><pre>
#: en/articles/lpi-101-administration-p2.xml:1157
#, no-wrap
msgid "Using kill to obliterate a process"
msgstr ""

#. type: Content of: <guide><chapter><section><body><pre>
#: en/articles/lpi-101-administration-p2.xml:1158
#, no-wrap
msgid ""
"$ <i>kill 16224</i>\n"
"$ <i>jobs -l</i>\n"
"[2]+ 16224 Stopped (signal)        xeyes -center blue\n"
"$ <i>kill -s SIGKILL</i>\n"
"$ <i>jobs -l</i>\n"
"[2]+ 16224 Interrupt               xeyes -center blue\n"
msgstr ""

#. type: Content of: <guide><chapter><section><title>
#: en/articles/lpi-101-administration-p2.xml:1169
#, no-wrap
msgid "nohup"
msgstr ""

#. type: Content of: <guide><chapter><section><body><p>
#: en/articles/lpi-101-administration-p2.xml:1173
#, no-wrap
msgid ""
"The terminal where you start a job is called the job's controlling terminal.\n"
"Some shells (not bash by default), will deliver a SIGHUP signal to backgrounded\n"
"jobs when you logout, causing them to quit. To protect processes from this\n"
"behavior, use the nohup when you start the process:\n"
msgstr ""

#. type: Attribute 'caption' of: <guide><chapter><section><body><pre>
#: en/articles/lpi-101-administration-p2.xml:1179
#, no-wrap
msgid "nohup in action"
msgstr ""

#. type: Content of: <guide><chapter><section><body><pre>
#: en/articles/lpi-101-administration-p2.xml:1180
#, no-wrap
msgid ""
"$ <i>nohup make &amp;</i>\n"
"[1] 15632\n"
"$ <i>exit</i>\n"
msgstr ""

#. type: Content of: <guide><chapter><section><title>
#: en/articles/lpi-101-administration-p2.xml:1188
#, no-wrap
msgid "Using ps to list processes"
msgstr ""

#. type: Content of: <guide><chapter><section><body><p>
#: en/articles/lpi-101-administration-p2.xml:1192
#, no-wrap
msgid ""
"The <c>jobs</c> command we were using earlier only lists processes that were\n"
"started from your bash session. To see all the processes on your system, use\n"
"<c>ps</c> with the <c>a</c> and <c>x</c> options together:\n"
msgstr ""

#. type: Attribute 'caption' of: <guide><chapter><section><body><pre>
#: en/articles/lpi-101-administration-p2.xml:1197
#, no-wrap
msgid "ps with ax"
msgstr ""

#. type: Content of: <guide><chapter><section><body><pre>
#: en/articles/lpi-101-administration-p2.xml:1198
#, no-wrap
msgid ""
"$ <i>ps ax</i>\n"
"  PID TTY      STAT   TIME COMMAND\n"
"    1 ?        S      0:04 init [3]\n"
"    2 ?        SW     0:11 [keventd]\n"
"    3 ?        SWN    0:13 [ksoftirqd_CPU0]\n"
"    4 ?        SW     2:33 [kswapd]\n"
"    5 ?        SW     0:00 [bdflush]\n"
msgstr ""

#. type: Content of: <guide><chapter><section><body><p>
#: en/articles/lpi-101-administration-p2.xml:1208
#, no-wrap
msgid ""
"I've only listed the first few because it is usually a very long list. This\n"
"gives you a snapshot of what the whole machine is doing, but is a lot of\n"
"information to sift through. If you were to leave off the <c>ax</c>, you would\n"
"see only processes that are owned by you, and that have a controlling terminal.\n"
"The command <c>ps x</c> would show you all your processes, even those without a\n"
"controlling terminal. If you were to use <c>ps a</c>, you would get the list of\n"
"everybody's processes that are attached to a terminal.\n"
msgstr ""

#. type: Content of: <guide><chapter><section><title>
#: en/articles/lpi-101-administration-p2.xml:1220
#, no-wrap
msgid "Seeing the forest and the trees"
msgstr ""

#. type: Content of: <guide><chapter><section><body><p>
#: en/articles/lpi-101-administration-p2.xml:1224
#, no-wrap
msgid ""
"You can also list different information about each process. The <c>--forest</c>\n"
"option makes it easy to see the process hierarchy, which will give you an\n"
"indication of how the various processes on your system interrelate. When a\n"
"process starts a new process, that new process is called a \"child\" process. In\n"
"a <c>--forest</c> listing, parents appear on the left, and children appear as\n"
"branches to the right:\n"
msgstr ""

#. type: Attribute 'caption' of: <guide><chapter><section><body><pre>
#: en/articles/lpi-101-administration-p2.xml:1232
#, no-wrap
msgid "Using forest"
msgstr ""

#. type: Content of: <guide><chapter><section><body><pre>
#: en/articles/lpi-101-administration-p2.xml:1233
#, no-wrap
msgid ""
"$ <i>ps x --forest</i>\n"
"  PID TTY      STAT   TIME COMMAND\n"
"  927 pts/1    S      0:00 bash\n"
" 6690 pts/1    S      0:00  \\_ bash\n"
"26909 pts/1    R      0:00      \\_ ps x --forest\n"
"19930 pts/4    S      0:01 bash\n"
"25740 pts/4    S      0:04  \\_ vi processes.txt\n"
msgstr ""

#. type: Content of: <guide><chapter><section><title>
#: en/articles/lpi-101-administration-p2.xml:1245
#, no-wrap
msgid "The \"u\" and \"l\" ps options"
msgstr ""

#. type: Content of: <guide><chapter><section><body><p>
#: en/articles/lpi-101-administration-p2.xml:1249
#, no-wrap
msgid ""
"The <c>u</c> or <c>l</c> options can also be added to any combination of\n"
"<c>a</c> and <c>x</c> in order to include more information about each process:\n"
msgstr ""

#. type: Attribute 'caption' of: <guide><chapter><section><body><pre>
#: en/articles/lpi-101-administration-p2.xml:1253
#, no-wrap
msgid "Option au"
msgstr ""

#. type: Content of: <guide><chapter><section><body><pre>
#: en/articles/lpi-101-administration-p2.xml:1254
#, no-wrap
msgid ""
"$ <i>ps au</i>\n"
"USER       PID %CPU %MEM   VSZ  RSS TTY      STAT START   TIME COMMAND\n"
"agriffis   403  0.0  0.0  2484   72 tty1     S     2001   0:00 -bash\n"
"chouser    404  0.0  0.0  2508   92 tty2     S     2001   0:00 -bash\n"
"root       408  0.0  0.0  1308  248 tty6     S     2001   0:00 /sbin/agetty 3\n"
"agriffis   434  0.0  0.0  1008    4 tty1     S     2001   0:00 /bin/sh /usr/X\n"
"chouser    927  0.0  0.0  2540   96 pts/1    S     2001   0:00 bash\n"
msgstr ""

#. type: Attribute 'caption' of: <guide><chapter><section><body><pre>
#: en/articles/lpi-101-administration-p2.xml:1263
#, no-wrap
msgid "Option al"
msgstr ""

#. type: Content of: <guide><chapter><section><body><pre>
#: en/articles/lpi-101-administration-p2.xml:1264
#, no-wrap
msgid ""
"$ <i>ps al</i>\n"
"  F   UID   PID  PPID PRI  NI   VSZ  RSS WCHAN  STAT TTY        TIME COMMAND\n"
"100  1001   403     1   9   0  2484   72 wait4  S    tty1       0:00 -bash\n"
"100  1000   404     1   9   0  2508   92 wait4  S    tty2       0:00 -bash\n"
"000     0   408     1   9   0  1308  248 read_c S    tty6       0:00 /sbin/ag\n"
"000  1001   434   403   9   0  1008    4 wait4  S    tty1       0:00 /bin/sh\n"
"000  1000   927   652   9   0  2540   96 wait4  S    pts/1      0:00 bash\n"
msgstr ""

#. type: Content of: <guide><chapter><section><title>
#: en/articles/lpi-101-administration-p2.xml:1276
#, no-wrap
msgid "Using top"
msgstr ""

#. type: Content of: <guide><chapter><section><body><p>
#: en/articles/lpi-101-administration-p2.xml:1280
#, no-wrap
msgid ""
"If you find yourself running ps several times in a row, trying to watch things\n"
"change, what you probably want is <c>top</c>. <c>top</c> displays a\n"
"continuously updated process listing, along with some useful summary\n"
"information:\n"
msgstr ""

#. type: Attribute 'caption' of: <guide><chapter><section><body><pre>
#: en/articles/lpi-101-administration-p2.xml:1286
#, no-wrap
msgid "top"
msgstr ""

#. type: Content of: <guide><chapter><section><body><pre>
#: en/articles/lpi-101-administration-p2.xml:1287
#, no-wrap
msgid ""
"$ <i>top</i>\n"
" 10:02pm  up 19 days,  6:24,  8 users,  load average: 0.04, 0.05, 0.00\n"
"75 processes: 74 sleeping, 1 running, 0 zombie, 0 stopped\n"
"CPU states:  1.3% user,  2.5% system,  0.0% nice, 96.0% idle\n"
"Mem:   256020K av,  226580K used,   29440K free,       0K shrd,    3804K buff\n"
"Swap:  136544K av,   80256K used,   56288K free                  101760K cached\n"
"\n"
"  PID USER     PRI  NI  SIZE  RSS SHARE STAT  LIB %CPU %MEM   TIME COMMAND\n"
"  628 root      16   0  213M  31M  2304 S       0  1.9 12.5  91:43 X\n"
"26934 chouser   17   0  1272 1272  1076 R       0  1.1  0.4   0:00 top\n"
"  652 chouser   11   0 12016 8840  1604 S       0  0.5  3.4   3:52 gnome-termin\n"
"  641 chouser    9   0  2936 2808  1416 S       0  0.1  1.0   2:13 sawfish\n"
msgstr ""

#. type: Content of: <guide><chapter><section><title>
#: en/articles/lpi-101-administration-p2.xml:1304
#, no-wrap
msgid "nice"
msgstr ""

#. type: Content of: <guide><chapter><section><body><p>
#: en/articles/lpi-101-administration-p2.xml:1308
#, no-wrap
msgid ""
"Each processes has a priority setting that Linux uses to determine how CPU\n"
"timeslices are shared. You can set the priority of a process by starting it\n"
"with the <c>nice</c> command:\n"
msgstr ""

#. type: Attribute 'caption' of: <guide><chapter><section><body><pre>
#: en/articles/lpi-101-administration-p2.xml:1313
#, no-wrap
msgid "nicing a process"
msgstr ""

#. type: Content of: <guide><chapter><section><body><pre>
#: en/articles/lpi-101-administration-p2.xml:1314
#, no-wrap
msgid "$ <i>nice -n 10 oggenc /tmp/song.wav</i>\n"
msgstr ""

#. type: Content of: <guide><chapter><section><body><p>
#: en/articles/lpi-101-administration-p2.xml:1318
#, no-wrap
msgid ""
"Since the priority setting is called <c>nice</c>, it should be easy to remember\n"
"that a higher value will be nice to other processes, allowing them to get\n"
"priority access to the CPU. By default, processes are started with a setting of\n"
"0, so the setting of 10 above means oggenc will readily give up the CPU to\n"
"other processes. Generally, this means that oggenc will allow other processes\n"
"to run at their normal speed, regardless of how CPU-hungry oggenc happens to\n"
"be. You can see these niceness levels under the NI column in the ps and top\n"
"listings above.\n"
msgstr ""

#. type: Content of: <guide><chapter><section><title>
#: en/articles/lpi-101-administration-p2.xml:1331
#, no-wrap
msgid "renice"
msgstr ""

#. type: Content of: <guide><chapter><section><body><p>
#: en/articles/lpi-101-administration-p2.xml:1335
#, no-wrap
msgid ""
"The <c>nice</c> command can only change the priority of a process when you\n"
"start it. If you want to change the niceness setting of a running process, use\n"
"<c>renice</c>:\n"
msgstr ""

#. type: Attribute 'caption' of: <guide><chapter><section><body><pre>
#: en/articles/lpi-101-administration-p2.xml:1340
#, no-wrap
msgid "using renice"
msgstr ""

#. type: Content of: <guide><chapter><section><body><pre>
#: en/articles/lpi-101-administration-p2.xml:1341
#, no-wrap
msgid ""
"$ <i>ps l 641</i>\n"
"  F   UID   PID  PPID PRI  NI   VSZ  RSS WCHAN  STAT TTY        TIME COMMAND\n"
"000  1000   641     1   9   0  5876 2808 do_sel S    ?          2:14 sawfish\n"
"$ <i>renice 10 641</i>\n"
"641: old priority 0, new priority 10\n"
"$ <i>ps l 641</i>\n"
"  F   UID   PID  PPID PRI  NI   VSZ  RSS WCHAN  STAT TTY        TIME COMMAND\n"
"000  1000   641     1   9  10  5876 2808 do_sel S    ?          2:14 sawfish\n"
msgstr ""

#. type: Content of: <guide><chapter><title>
#: en/articles/lpi-101-administration-p2.xml:1356
#, no-wrap
msgid "Text processing"
msgstr ""

#. type: Content of: <guide><chapter><section><title>
#: en/articles/lpi-101-administration-p2.xml:1358
#, no-wrap
msgid "Redirection revisited"
msgstr ""

#. type: Content of: <guide><chapter><section><body><p>
#: en/articles/lpi-101-administration-p2.xml:1362
#, no-wrap
msgid ""
"Earlier in this tutorial series, we saw an example of how to use the <c>></c>\n"
"operator to redirect the output of a command to a file, as follows:\n"
msgstr ""

#. type: Attribute 'caption' of: <guide><chapter><section><body><pre>
#: en/articles/lpi-101-administration-p2.xml:1366
#, no-wrap
msgid "Use of the > operator"
msgstr ""

#. type: Content of: <guide><chapter><section><body><pre>
#: en/articles/lpi-101-administration-p2.xml:1367
#, no-wrap
msgid "$ <i>echo \"firstfile\" > copyme</i>\n"
msgstr ""

#. type: Content of: <guide><chapter><section><body><p>
#: en/articles/lpi-101-administration-p2.xml:1371
#, no-wrap
msgid ""
"In addition to redirecting output to a file, we can also take advantage of a\n"
"powerful shell feature called pipes. Using pipes, we can pass the output of one\n"
"command to the input of another command. Consider the following example:\n"
msgstr ""

#. type: Attribute 'caption' of: <guide><chapter><section><body><pre>
#: en/articles/lpi-101-administration-p2.xml:1376
#, no-wrap
msgid "Introducing pipes"
msgstr ""

#. type: Content of: <guide><chapter><section><body><pre>
#: en/articles/lpi-101-administration-p2.xml:1377
#, no-wrap
msgid ""
"$ <i>echo \"hi there\" | wc</i>\n"
"      1       2       9\n"
msgstr ""

#. type: Content of: <guide><chapter><section><body><p>
#: en/articles/lpi-101-administration-p2.xml:1382
#, no-wrap
msgid ""
"The <c>|</c> character is used to connect the output of the command on the left\n"
"to the input of the command on the right. In the example above, the <c>echo</c>\n"
"command prints out the string \"hi there\" followed by a linefeed. That output\n"
"would normally appear on the terminal, but the pipe redirects it into the\n"
"<c>wc</c> command, which displays the number of lines, words, and characters in\n"
"its input.\n"
msgstr ""

#. type: Content of: <guide><chapter><section><title>
#: en/articles/lpi-101-administration-p2.xml:1393
#, no-wrap
msgid "A pipe example"
msgstr ""

#. type: Content of: <guide><chapter><section><body><p>
#: en/articles/lpi-101-administration-p2.xml:1397
#, no-wrap
msgid "Here is another simple example:\n"
msgstr ""

#. type: Attribute 'caption' of: <guide><chapter><section><body><pre>
#: en/articles/lpi-101-administration-p2.xml:1400
#, no-wrap
msgid "pipes in action"
msgstr ""

#. type: Content of: <guide><chapter><section><body><pre>
#: en/articles/lpi-101-administration-p2.xml:1401
#, no-wrap
msgid "$ <i>ls -s | sort -n</i>\n"
msgstr ""

#. type: Content of: <guide><chapter><section><body><p>
#: en/articles/lpi-101-administration-p2.xml:1405
#, no-wrap
msgid ""
"In this case, <c>ls -s</c> would normally print a listing of the current\n"
"directory on the terminal, preceding each file with its size. But instead we've\n"
"piped the output into <c>sort -n</c>, which sorts the output numerically. This\n"
"is a really useful way to find large files in your home directory!\n"
msgstr ""

#. type: Content of: <guide><chapter><section><body><p>
#: en/articles/lpi-101-administration-p2.xml:1412
#, no-wrap
msgid ""
"The following examples are more complex, but they demonstrate the power that\n"
"can be harnessed using pipes. We're going to throw out some commands we haven't\n"
"covered yet, but don't let that slow you down. Concentrate instead on\n"
"understanding how pipes work so you can employ them in your daily Linux tasks.\n"
msgstr ""

#. type: Content of: <guide><chapter><section><title>
#: en/articles/lpi-101-administration-p2.xml:1421
#, no-wrap
msgid "The decompression pipeline"
msgstr ""

#. type: Content of: <guide><chapter><section><body><p>
#: en/articles/lpi-101-administration-p2.xml:1425
#, no-wrap
msgid "Normally to decompress and untar a file, you might do the following:\n"
msgstr ""

#. type: Attribute 'caption' of: <guide><chapter><section><body><pre>
#: en/articles/lpi-101-administration-p2.xml:1428
#, no-wrap
msgid "Untarring a file"
msgstr ""

#. type: Content of: <guide><chapter><section><body><pre>
#: en/articles/lpi-101-administration-p2.xml:1429
#, no-wrap
msgid ""
"$ <i>bzip2 -d linux-2.4.16.tar.bz2</i>\n"
"$ <i>tar xvf linux-2.4.16.tar</i>\n"
msgstr ""

#. type: Content of: <guide><chapter><section><body><p>
#: en/articles/lpi-101-administration-p2.xml:1434
#, no-wrap
msgid ""
"The downside of this method is that it requires the creation of an\n"
"intermediate, uncompressed file on your disk. Since <c>tar</c> has the ability\n"
"to read directly from its input (instead of specifying a file), we could\n"
"produce the same end-result using a pipeline:\n"
msgstr ""

#. type: Attribute 'caption' of: <guide><chapter><section><body><pre>
#: en/articles/lpi-101-administration-p2.xml:1440
#, no-wrap
msgid "untarring using a pipeline"
msgstr ""

#. type: Content of: <guide><chapter><section><body><pre>
#: en/articles/lpi-101-administration-p2.xml:1441
#, no-wrap
msgid "$ <i>bzip2 -dc linux-2.4.16.tar.bz2 | tar xvf -</i>\n"
msgstr ""

#. type: Content of: <guide><chapter><section><body><p>
#: en/articles/lpi-101-administration-p2.xml:1445
#, no-wrap
msgid ""
"Woo hoo! Our compressed tarball has been extracted and we didn't need an\n"
"intermediate file.\n"
msgstr ""

#. type: Content of: <guide><chapter><section><title>
#: en/articles/lpi-101-administration-p2.xml:1452
#, no-wrap
msgid "A longer pipeline"
msgstr ""

#. type: Content of: <guide><chapter><section><body><p>
#: en/articles/lpi-101-administration-p2.xml:1456
#, no-wrap
msgid "Here's another pipeline example:\n"
msgstr ""

#. type: Attribute 'caption' of: <guide><chapter><section><body><pre>
#: en/articles/lpi-101-administration-p2.xml:1459
#, no-wrap
msgid "Longer pipelines"
msgstr ""

#. type: Content of: <guide><chapter><section><body><pre>
#: en/articles/lpi-101-administration-p2.xml:1460
#, no-wrap
msgid "$ <i>cat myfile.txt | sort | uniq | wc -l</i>\n"
msgstr ""

#. type: Content of: <guide><chapter><section><body><p>
#: en/articles/lpi-101-administration-p2.xml:1464
#, no-wrap
msgid ""
"We use <c>cat</c> to feed the contents of <path>myfile.txt</path> to the\n"
"<c>sort</c> command. When the <c>sort</c> command receives the input, it sorts\n"
"all input lines so that they are in alphabetical order, and then sends the\n"
"output to <c>uniq</c>. <c>uniq</c> removes any duplicate lines (and requires\n"
"its input to be sorted, by the way,) sending the scrubbed output to <c>wc\n"
"-l</c>. We've seen the <c>wc</c> command earlier, but without command-line\n"
"options. When given the <c>-l</c> option, it only prints the number of lines in\n"
"its input, instead of also including words and characters. You'll see that this\n"
"pipeline will print out the number of unique (non-identical) lines in a text\n"
"file.\n"
msgstr ""

#. type: Content of: <guide><chapter><section><body><p>
#: en/articles/lpi-101-administration-p2.xml:1477
#, no-wrap
msgid ""
"Try creating a couple of test files with your favorite text editor and use this\n"
"pipeline to see what results you get.\n"
msgstr ""

#. type: Content of: <guide><chapter><section><title>
#: en/articles/lpi-101-administration-p2.xml:1484
#, no-wrap
msgid "The text processing whirlwind begins"
msgstr ""

#. type: Content of: <guide><chapter><section><body><p>
#: en/articles/lpi-101-administration-p2.xml:1488
#, no-wrap
msgid ""
"Now we embark on a whirlwind tour of the standard Linux text processing\n"
"commands. Because we're covering a lot of material in this tutorial, we don't\n"
"have the space to provide examples for every command. Instead, we encourage you\n"
"to read each command's man page (by typing <c>man echo</c>, for example) and\n"
"learn how each command and it's options work by spending some time playing with\n"
"each one. As a rule, these commands print the results of any text processing to\n"
"the terminal rather than modifying any specified files. After we take our\n"
"whirlwind tour of the standard Linux text processing commands, we'll take a\n"
"closer look at output and input redirection. So yes, there is light at the end\n"
"of the tunnel :)\n"
msgstr ""

#. type: Content of: <guide><chapter><section><body><p>
#: en/articles/lpi-101-administration-p2.xml:1501
#, no-wrap
msgid ""
"<c>echo</c> prints its arguments to the terminal. Use the <c>-e</c> option if\n"
"you want to embed backslash escape sequences; for example <c>echo -e\n"
"\"foo\\nfoo\"</c> will print foo, then a newline, and then foo again. Use the\n"
"<c>-n</c> option to tell echo to omit the trailing newline that is appended to\n"
"the output by default.\n"
msgstr ""

#. type: Content of: <guide><chapter><section><body><p>
#: en/articles/lpi-101-administration-p2.xml:1509
#, no-wrap
msgid ""
"<c>cat</c> will print the contents of the files specified as arguments to the\n"
"terminal. Handy as the first command of a pipeline, for example, <c>cat foo.txt\n"
"| blah</c>.\n"
msgstr ""

#. type: Content of: <guide><chapter><section><body><p>
#: en/articles/lpi-101-administration-p2.xml:1515
#, no-wrap
msgid ""
"<c>sort</c> will print the contents of the file specified on the command line\n"
"in alphabetical order. Of course, <c>sort</c> also accepts piped input. Type\n"
"<c>man sort</c> to familiarize yourself with its various options that control\n"
"sorting behavior.\n"
msgstr ""

#. type: Content of: <guide><chapter><section><body><p>
#: en/articles/lpi-101-administration-p2.xml:1522
#, no-wrap
msgid ""
"<c>uniq</c> takes an <e>already-sorted</e> file or stream of data (via a\n"
"pipeline) and removes duplicate lines.\n"
msgstr ""

#. type: Content of: <guide><chapter><section><body><p>
#: en/articles/lpi-101-administration-p2.xml:1527
#, no-wrap
msgid ""
"<c>wc</c> prints out the number of lines, words, and bytes in the specified\n"
"file or in the input stream (from a pipeline). Type <c>man wc</c> to learn how\n"
"to fine-tune what counts are displayed.\n"
msgstr ""

#. type: Content of: <guide><chapter><section><body><p>
#: en/articles/lpi-101-administration-p2.xml:1533
#, no-wrap
msgid ""
"<c>head</c> prints out the first ten lines of a file or stream. Use the\n"
"<c>-n</c> option to specify how many lines should be displayed.\n"
msgstr ""

#. type: Content of: <guide><chapter><section><body><p>
#: en/articles/lpi-101-administration-p2.xml:1538
#, no-wrap
msgid ""
"<c>tail</c> prints out the last ten lines of a file or stream. Use the\n"
"<c>-n</c> option to specify how many lines should be displayed.\n"
msgstr ""

#. type: Content of: <guide><chapter><section><body><p>
#: en/articles/lpi-101-administration-p2.xml:1543
#, no-wrap
msgid ""
"<c>tac</c> is like <c>cat</c>, but prints all lines in reverse order; in other\n"
"words, the last line is printed first.\n"
msgstr ""

#. type: Content of: <guide><chapter><section><body><p>
#: en/articles/lpi-101-administration-p2.xml:1548
#, no-wrap
msgid ""
"<c>expand</c> converts input tabs to spaces. Use the <c>-t</c> option to\n"
"specify the tabstop.\n"
msgstr ""

#. type: Content of: <guide><chapter><section><body><p>
#: en/articles/lpi-101-administration-p2.xml:1553
#, no-wrap
msgid ""
"<c>unexpand</c> converts input spaces to tabs. Use the <c>-t</c> option to\n"
"specify the tabstop.\n"
msgstr ""

#. type: Content of: <guide><chapter><section><body><p>
#: en/articles/lpi-101-administration-p2.xml:1558
#, no-wrap
msgid ""
"<c>cut</c> is used to extract character-delimited fields from each line of an\n"
"input file or stream.\n"
msgstr ""

#. type: Content of: <guide><chapter><section><body><p>
#: en/articles/lpi-101-administration-p2.xml:1563
#, no-wrap
msgid ""
"The <c>nl</c> command adds a line number to every line of input. Useful for\n"
"printouts.\n"
msgstr ""

#. type: Content of: <guide><chapter><section><body><p>
#: en/articles/lpi-101-administration-p2.xml:1568
#, no-wrap
msgid ""
"<c>pr</c> is used to break files into multiple pages of output; typically used\n"
"for printing.\n"
msgstr ""

#. type: Content of: <guide><chapter><section><body><p>
#: en/articles/lpi-101-administration-p2.xml:1573
#, no-wrap
msgid ""
"<c>tr</c> is a character translation tool; it's used to map certain characters\n"
"in the input stream to certain other characters in the output stream.\n"
msgstr ""

#. type: Content of: <guide><chapter><section><body><p>
#: en/articles/lpi-101-administration-p2.xml:1578
#, no-wrap
msgid ""
"<c>sed</c> is a powerful stream-oriented text editor. You can learn more about\n"
"sed in the following IBM developerWorks articles:\n"
msgstr ""

