#: en/articles/lpi-101-administration-p2.xml:1585
#, no-wrap
msgid "<uri link=\"/doc/en/articles/l-sed3.xml\">Sed by example, Part 3</uri>"
msgstr ""

#. type: Content of: <guide><chapter><section><body><p>
#: en/articles/lpi-101-administration-p2.xml:1589
#, no-wrap
msgid ""
"If you're planning to take the LPI exam, be sure to read the first two articles\n"
"of this series.\n"
msgstr ""

#. type: Content of: <guide><chapter><section><body><p>
#: en/articles/lpi-101-administration-p2.xml:1594
#, no-wrap
msgid ""
"<c>awk</c> is a handy line-oriented text-processing language. To learn more\n"
"about awk, read the following IBM developerWorks articles:\n"
msgstr ""

#. type: Content of: <guide><chapter><section><body><ul><li>
#: en/articles/lpi-101-administration-p2.xml:1599
#, no-wrap
msgid "<uri link=\"/doc/en/articles/l-awk1.xml\">Awk by example, Part 1</uri>"
msgstr ""

#. type: Content of: <guide><chapter><section><body><ul><li>
#: en/articles/lpi-101-administration-p2.xml:1600
#, no-wrap
msgid "<uri link=\"/doc/en/articles/l-awk2.xml\">Awk by example, Part 2</uri>"
msgstr ""

#. type: Content of: <guide><chapter><section><body><ul><li>
#: en/articles/lpi-101-administration-p2.xml:1601
#, no-wrap
msgid ""
"<uri link=\"/doc/en/articles/l-awk3.xml\">Awk by example, Part 3</uri>\n"
"  "
msgstr ""

#. type: Content of: <guide><chapter><section><body><p>
#: en/articles/lpi-101-administration-p2.xml:1606
#, no-wrap
msgid ""
"<c>od</c> is designed to transform the input stream into a octal or hex \"dump\"\n"
"format.\n"
msgstr ""

#. type: Content of: <guide><chapter><section><body><p>
#: en/articles/lpi-101-administration-p2.xml:1611
#, no-wrap
msgid ""
"<c>split</c> is a command used to split a larger file into many smaller-sized,\n"
"more manageable chunks.\n"
msgstr ""

#. type: Content of: <guide><chapter><section><body><p>
#: en/articles/lpi-101-administration-p2.xml:1616
#, no-wrap
msgid ""
"<c>fmt</c> will reformat paragraphs so that wrapping is done at the margin.\n"
"These days it's less useful since this ability is built into most text editors,\n"
"but it's still a good one to know.\n"
msgstr ""

#. type: Content of: <guide><chapter><section><body><p>
#: en/articles/lpi-101-administration-p2.xml:1622
#, no-wrap
msgid ""
"<c>paste</c> takes two or more files as input, concatenates each sequential\n"
"line from the input files, and outputs the resulting lines. It can be useful to\n"
"create tables or columns of text.\n"
msgstr ""

#. type: Content of: <guide><chapter><section><body><p>
#: en/articles/lpi-101-administration-p2.xml:1628
#, no-wrap
msgid ""
"<c>join</c> is similar to paste, but it uses a field (by default the first) in\n"
"each input line to match up what should be combined on a single line.\n"
msgstr ""

#. type: Content of: <guide><chapter><section><body><p>
#: en/articles/lpi-101-administration-p2.xml:1633
#, no-wrap
msgid ""
"<c>tee</c> prints its input both to a file and to the screen. This is useful\n"
"when you want to create a log of something, but you also want to see it on the\n"
"screen.\n"
msgstr ""

#. type: Content of: <guide><chapter><section><title>
#: en/articles/lpi-101-administration-p2.xml:1641
#, no-wrap
msgid "Whirlwind over! Redirection"
msgstr ""

#. type: Content of: <guide><chapter><section><body><p>
#: en/articles/lpi-101-administration-p2.xml:1645
#, no-wrap
msgid ""
"Similar to using <c>&gt;</c> on the bash command line, you can also use\n"
"<c>&lt;</c> to redirect a file into a command. For many commands, you can\n"
"simply specify the filename on the command line, however some commands only\n"
"work from standard input.\n"
msgstr ""

#. type: Content of: <guide><chapter><section><body><p>
#: en/articles/lpi-101-administration-p2.xml:1652
#, no-wrap
msgid ""
"Bash and other shells support the concept of a \"herefile.\" This allows you to\n"
"specify the input to a command in the lines following the command invocation,\n"
"terminating it with a sentinal value. This is easiest shown through an example:\n"
msgstr ""

#. type: Attribute 'caption' of: <guide><chapter><section><body><pre>
#: en/articles/lpi-101-administration-p2.xml:1657
#, no-wrap
msgid "Redirection in action"
msgstr ""

#. type: Content of: <guide><chapter><section><body><pre>
#: en/articles/lpi-101-administration-p2.xml:1658
#, no-wrap
msgid ""
"$ <i>sort &lt;&lt;END</i>\n"
"apple\n"
"cranberry\n"
"banana\n"
"END\n"
"apple\n"
"banana\n"
"cranberry\n"
msgstr ""

#. type: Content of: <guide><chapter><section><body><p>
#: en/articles/lpi-101-administration-p2.xml:1669
#, no-wrap
msgid ""
"In the example above, we typed the words apple, cranberry and banana, followed\n"
"by \"END\" to signify the end of the input. The <c>sort</c> program then returned\n"
"our words in alphabetical order.\n"
msgstr ""

#. type: Content of: <guide><chapter><section><title>
#: en/articles/lpi-101-administration-p2.xml:1677
#, no-wrap
msgid "Using &gt;&gt;"
msgstr ""

#. type: Content of: <guide><chapter><section><body><p>
#: en/articles/lpi-101-administration-p2.xml:1681
#, no-wrap
msgid ""
"You would expect <c>&gt;&gt;</c> to be somehow analogous to <c>&lt;&lt;</c>,\n"
"but it isn't really. It simply means to append the output to a file, rather\n"
"than overwrite as <c>&gt;</c> would. For example:\n"
msgstr ""

#. type: Attribute 'caption' of: <guide><chapter><section><body><pre>
#: en/articles/lpi-101-administration-p2.xml:1686
#, no-wrap
msgid "Redirecting to a file"
msgstr ""

#. type: Content of: <guide><chapter><section><body><pre>
#: en/articles/lpi-101-administration-p2.xml:1687
#, no-wrap
msgid ""
"$ <i>echo Hi &gt; myfile</i>\n"
"$ <i>echo there. &gt; myfile</i>\n"
"$ <i>cat myfile</i>\n"
"there.\n"
msgstr ""

#. type: Content of: <guide><chapter><section><body><p>
#: en/articles/lpi-101-administration-p2.xml:1694
#, no-wrap
msgid "Oops! We lost the \"Hi\" portion! What we meant was this:\n"
msgstr ""

#. type: Attribute 'caption' of: <guide><chapter><section><body><pre>
#: en/articles/lpi-101-administration-p2.xml:1697
#, no-wrap
msgid "Appending to a file"
msgstr ""

#. type: Content of: <guide><chapter><section><body><pre>
#: en/articles/lpi-101-administration-p2.xml:1698
#, no-wrap
msgid ""
"$ <i>echo Hi &gt; myfile</i>\n"
"$ <i>echo there. &gt;&gt; myfile</i>\n"
"$ <i>cat myfile</i>\n"
"Hi\n"
"there.\n"
msgstr ""

#. type: Content of: <guide><chapter><section><body><p>
#: en/articles/lpi-101-administration-p2.xml:1706
#, no-wrap
msgid "Much better!\n"
msgstr ""

#. type: Content of: <guide><chapter><title>
#: en/articles/lpi-101-administration-p2.xml:1714
#, no-wrap
msgid "Kernel Modules"
msgstr ""

#. type: Content of: <guide><chapter><section><title>
#: en/articles/lpi-101-administration-p2.xml:1716
#, no-wrap
msgid "Meet \"uname\""
msgstr ""

#. type: Content of: <guide><chapter><section><body><p>
#: en/articles/lpi-101-administration-p2.xml:1720
#, no-wrap
msgid ""
"The <c>uname</c> command provides a variety of interesting information about\n"
"your system. Here's what is displayed on my development workstation when I type\n"
"<c>uname -a</c> which tells the <c>uname</c> command to print out all of its\n"
"information in one swoop:\n"
msgstr ""

#. type: Attribute 'caption' of: <guide><chapter><section><body><pre>
#: en/articles/lpi-101-administration-p2.xml:1726
#, no-wrap
msgid "uname -a"
msgstr ""

#. type: Content of: <guide><chapter><section><body><pre>
#: en/articles/lpi-101-administration-p2.xml:1727
#, no-wrap
msgid ""
"$ <i>uname -a</i>\n"
"Linux inventor 2.4.20-gaming-r1 #1 Fri Apr 11 18:33:35 MDT 2003 i686 AMD Athlon(tm) XP 2100+ AuthenticAMD GNU/Linux\n"
msgstr ""

#. type: Content of: <guide><chapter><section><title>
#: en/articles/lpi-101-administration-p2.xml:1734
#, no-wrap
msgid "More uname madness"
msgstr ""

#. type: Content of: <guide><chapter><section><body><p>
#: en/articles/lpi-101-administration-p2.xml:1738
#, no-wrap
msgid "Now, let's look at the information that <c>uname</c> provides\n"
msgstr ""

#. type: Attribute 'caption' of: <guide><chapter><section><body><pre>
#: en/articles/lpi-101-administration-p2.xml:1741
#, no-wrap
msgid "uname info"
msgstr ""

#. type: Content of: <guide><chapter><section><body><pre>
#: en/articles/lpi-101-administration-p2.xml:1742
#, no-wrap
msgid ""
"info. option                    arg     example\n"
"kernel name                     -s      \"Linux\"\n"
"hostname                        -n      \"inventor\"\n"
"kernel release                  -r      \"2.4.20-gaming-r1\"\n"
"kernel version                  -v      \"#1 Fri Apr 11 18:33:35 MDT 2003\"\n"
"machine                         -m      \"i686\"\n"
"processor                       -p      \"AMD Athlon(tm) XP 2100+\"\n"
"hardware platform               -i      \"AuthenticAMD\"\n"
"operating system                -o      \"GNU/Linux\"\n"
msgstr ""

#. type: Content of: <guide><chapter><section><body><p>
#: en/articles/lpi-101-administration-p2.xml:1754
#, no-wrap
msgid "Intriguing! What does your <c>uname -a</c> command print out?\n"
msgstr ""

#. type: Content of: <guide><chapter><section><title>
#: en/articles/lpi-101-administration-p2.xml:1760
#, no-wrap
msgid "The kernel release"
msgstr ""

#. type: Content of: <guide><chapter><section><body><p>
#: en/articles/lpi-101-administration-p2.xml:1764
#, no-wrap
msgid ""
"Here's a magic trick. First, type <c>uname -r</c> to have the uname command\n"
"print out the release of the Linux kernel that's currently running.\n"
msgstr ""

#. type: Content of: <guide><chapter><section><body><p>
#: en/articles/lpi-101-administration-p2.xml:1769
#, no-wrap
msgid ""
"Now, look in the <path>/lib/modules</path> directory and --presto!-- I bet\n"
"you'll find a directory with that exact name! OK, not quite magic, but now may\n"
"be a good time to talk about the significance of the directories in\n"
"<path>/lib/modules</path> and explain what kernel modules are.\n"
msgstr ""

#. type: Content of: <guide><chapter><section><title>
#: en/articles/lpi-101-administration-p2.xml:1778
#, no-wrap
msgid "The kernel"
msgstr ""

#. type: Content of: <guide><chapter><section><body><p>
#: en/articles/lpi-101-administration-p2.xml:1782
#, no-wrap
msgid ""
"The Linux kernel is the heart of what is commonly referred to as \"Linux\" --\n"
"it's the piece of code that accesses your hardware directly and provides\n"
"abstractions so that regular old programs can run. Thanks to the kernel, your\n"
"text editor doesn't need to worry about whether it is writing to a SCSI or IDE\n"
"disk -- or even a RAM disk. It just writes to a filesystem, and the kernel\n"
"takes care of the rest.\n"
msgstr ""

#. type: Content of: <guide><chapter><section><title>
#: en/articles/lpi-101-administration-p2.xml:1793
#, no-wrap
msgid "Introducing kernel modules"
msgstr ""

#. type: Content of: <guide><chapter><section><body><p>
#: en/articles/lpi-101-administration-p2.xml:1797
#, no-wrap
msgid ""
"So, what are kernel modules? Well, they're parts of the kernel that have been\n"
"stored in a special format on disk. At your command, they can be loaded into\n"
"the running kernel and provide additional functionality.\n"
msgstr ""

#. type: Content of: <guide><chapter><section><body><p>
#: en/articles/lpi-101-administration-p2.xml:1803
#, no-wrap
msgid ""
"Because the kernel modules are loaded on demand, you can have your kernel\n"
"support a lot of additional functionality that you may not ordinarily want to\n"
"be enabled. But once in a blue moon, those kernel modules are likely to come in\n"
"quite handy and can be loaded -- often automatically -- to support that odd\n"
"filesystem or hardware device that you rarely use.\n"
msgstr ""

#. type: Content of: <guide><chapter><section><title>
#: en/articles/lpi-101-administration-p2.xml:1813
#, no-wrap
msgid "Kernel modules in a nutshell"
msgstr ""

#. type: Content of: <guide><chapter><section><body><p>
#: en/articles/lpi-101-administration-p2.xml:1817
#, no-wrap
msgid ""
"In sum, kernel modules allow for the running kernel to enable capabilities on\n"
"an on-demand basis. Without kernel modules, you'd have to compile a completely\n"
"new kernel and reboot in order for it to support something new.\n"
msgstr ""

#. type: Content of: <guide><chapter><section><title>
#: en/articles/lpi-101-administration-p2.xml:1825
#, no-wrap
msgid "lsmod"
msgstr ""

#. type: Content of: <guide><chapter><section><body><p>
#: en/articles/lpi-101-administration-p2.xml:1829
#, no-wrap
msgid ""
"To see what modules are currently loaded on your system, use the <c>lsmod</c>\n"
"command:\n"
msgstr ""

#. type: Attribute 'caption' of: <guide><chapter><section><body><pre>
#: en/articles/lpi-101-administration-p2.xml:1833
#, no-wrap
msgid "using lsmod"
msgstr ""

#. type: Content of: <guide><chapter><section><body><pre>
#: en/articles/lpi-101-administration-p2.xml:1834
#, no-wrap
msgid ""
"# <i>lsmod</i>\n"
"Module                  Size  Used by    Tainted: PF\n"
"vmnet                  20520   5\n"
"vmmon                  22484  11\n"
"nvidia               1547648  10\n"
"mousedev                3860   2\n"
"hid                    16772   0  (unused)\n"
"usbmouse                1848   0  (unused)\n"
"input                   3136   0  [mousedev hid usbmouse]\n"
"usb-ohci               15976   0  (unused)\n"
"ehci-hcd               13288   0  (unused)\n"
"emu10k1                64264   2\n"
"ac97_codec              9000   0  [emu10k1]\n"
"sound                  51508   0  [emu10k1]\n"
"usbcore                55168   1  [hid usbmouse usb-ohci ehci-hcd]\n"
msgstr ""

#. type: Content of: <guide><chapter><section><title>
#: en/articles/lpi-101-administration-p2.xml:1854
#, no-wrap
msgid "Modules listing"
msgstr ""

#. type: Content of: <guide><chapter><section><body><p>
#: en/articles/lpi-101-administration-p2.xml:1858
#, no-wrap
msgid ""
"As you can see, my system has quite a few modules loaded. the vmnet and vmmon\n"
"modules provide necessary functionality for my <uri\n"
"link=\"http://www.vmware.com/\">VMWare</uri> program, which allows me to run a\n"
"virtual PC in a window on my desktop. The \"nvidia\" module comes from <uri\n"
"link=\"http://www.nvidia.com/\">NVIDIA</uri> corporation and allows me to use my\n"
"high-performance 3D-accelerated graphics card under Linux whilst taking\n"
"advantage of its many neat features.\n"
msgstr ""

#. type: Content of: <guide><chapter><section><body><p>
#: en/articles/lpi-101-administration-p2.xml:1868
#, no-wrap
msgid ""
"Then I have a bunch of modules that are used to provide support for my\n"
"USB-based input devices -- namely \"mousedev,\" \"hid,\" \"usbmouse,\" \"input,\"\n"
"\"usb-ohci,\" \"ehci-hcd\" and \"usbcore.\" It often makes sense to configure your\n"
"kernel to provide USB support as modules. Why? Because USB devices are \"plug\n"
"and play,\" and when you have your USB support in modules, then you can go out\n"
"and buy a new USB device, plug it in to your system, and have the system\n"
"automatically load the appropriate modules to enable that device. It's a handy\n"
"way to do things.\n"
msgstr ""

#. type: Content of: <guide><chapter><section><title>
#: en/articles/lpi-101-administration-p2.xml:1881
#, no-wrap
msgid "Third-party modules"
msgstr ""

#. type: Content of: <guide><chapter><section><body><p>
#: en/articles/lpi-101-administration-p2.xml:1885
#, no-wrap
msgid ""
"Rounding out my list of modules are \"emu10k1,\" \"ac97_codec,\" and \"sound,\" which\n"
"together provide support for my SoundBlaster Audigy sound card.\n"
msgstr ""

#. type: Content of: <guide><chapter><section><body><p>
#: en/articles/lpi-101-administration-p2.xml:1890
#, no-wrap
msgid ""
"It should be noted that some of my kernel modules come from the kernel sources\n"
"themselves. For example, all the USB-related modules are compiled from the\n"
"standard Linux kernel sources. However, the nvidia, emu10k1 and VMWare-related\n"
"modules come from other sources. This highlights another major benefit of\n"
"kernel modules -- allowing third parties to provide much-needed kernel\n"
"functionality and allowing this functionality to \"plug in\" to a running Linux\n"
"kernel. No reboot necessary.\n"
msgstr ""

#. type: Content of: <guide><chapter><section><title>
#: en/articles/lpi-101-administration-p2.xml:1902
#, no-wrap
msgid "depmod and friends"
msgstr ""

#. type: Content of: <guide><chapter><section><body><p>
#: en/articles/lpi-101-administration-p2.xml:1906
#, no-wrap
msgid ""
"In my <path>/lib/modules/2.4.20-gaming-r1/</path> directory, I have a number of\n"
"files that start with the string \"modules.\":\n"
msgstr ""

#. type: Attribute 'caption' of: <guide><chapter><section><body><pre>
#: en/articles/lpi-101-administration-p2.xml:1910
#, no-wrap
msgid "other modules"
msgstr ""

#. type: Content of: <guide><chapter><section><body><pre>
#: en/articles/lpi-101-administration-p2.xml:1911
#, no-wrap
msgid ""
"$ <i>ls /lib/modules/2.4.20-gaming-r1/modules.*</i>\n"
"/lib/modules/2.4.20-gaming-r1/modules.dep\n"
"/lib/modules/2.4.20-gaming-r1/modules.generic_string\n"
"/lib/modules/2.4.20-gaming-r1/modules.ieee1394map\n"
"/lib/modules/2.4.20-gaming-r1/modules.isapnpmap\n"
"/lib/modules/2.4.20-gaming-r1/modules.parportmap\n"
"/lib/modules/2.4.20-gaming-r1/modules.pcimap\n"
"/lib/modules/2.4.20-gaming-r1/modules.pnpbiosmap\n"
"/lib/modules/2.4.20-gaming-r1/modules.usbmap\n"
msgstr ""

#. type: Content of: <guide><chapter><section><body><p>
#: en/articles/lpi-101-administration-p2.xml:1923
#, no-wrap
msgid ""
"These files contain some lots of dependency information. For one, they record\n"
"*dependency* information for modules -- some modules require other modules to\n"
"be loaded first before they will run. This information is recorded in these\n"
"files.\n"
msgstr ""

#. type: Content of: <guide><chapter><section><title>
#: en/articles/lpi-101-administration-p2.xml:1932
#, no-wrap
msgid "How you get modules"
msgstr ""

#. type: Content of: <guide><chapter><section><body><p>
#: en/articles/lpi-101-administration-p2.xml:1936
#, no-wrap
msgid ""
"Some kernel modules are designed to work with specific hardware devices, like\n"
"my \"emu10k1\" module which is for my SoundBlaster Audigy card. For these types\n"
"of modules, these files also record the PCI IDs and similar identifying marks\n"
"of the hardware devices that they support. This information can be used by\n"
"things like the \"hotplug\" scripts (which we'll take a look at in later\n"
"tutorials) to auto-detect hardware and load the appropriate module to support\n"
"said hardware automatically.\n"
msgstr ""

#. type: Content of: <guide><chapter><section><title>
#: en/articles/lpi-101-administration-p2.xml:1948
#, no-wrap
msgid "Using depmod"
msgstr ""

#. type: Content of: <guide><chapter><section><body><p>
#: en/articles/lpi-101-administration-p2.xml:1952
#, no-wrap
msgid ""
"If you ever install a new module, this dependency information may become out of\n"
"date. To make it fresh again, simply type <c>depmod -a</c>. The <c>depmod</c>\n"
"program will then scan all the modules in your directories in\n"
"<path>/lib/modules</path> and freshening the dependency information. It does\n"
"this by scanning the module files in <path>/lib/modules</path> and looking at\n"
"what are called \"symbols\" inside the modules.\n"
msgstr ""

#. type: Content of: <guide><chapter><section><title>
#: en/articles/lpi-101-administration-p2.xml:1963
#, no-wrap
msgid "Locating kernel modules"
msgstr ""

#. type: Content of: <guide><chapter><section><body><p>
#: en/articles/lpi-101-administration-p2.xml:1967
#, no-wrap
msgid ""
"So, what do kernel modules look like? For 2.4 kernels, they're typically any\n"
"file in the <path>/lib/modules</path> tree that ends in \".o\". To see all the\n"
"modules in <path>/lib/modules</path>, type the following:\n"
msgstr ""

#. type: Attribute 'caption' of: <guide><chapter><section><body><pre>
#: en/articles/lpi-101-administration-p2.xml:1972
#, no-wrap
msgid "kernel modules in /lib/modules"
msgstr ""

#. type: Content of: <guide><chapter><section><body><pre>
#: en/articles/lpi-101-administration-p2.xml:1973
#, no-wrap
msgid ""
"# <i>find /lib/modules -name '*.o'</i>\n"
"/lib/modules/2.4.20-gaming-r1/misc/vmmon.o\n"
"/lib/modules/2.4.20-gaming-r1/misc/vmnet.o\n"
"/lib/modules/2.4.20-gaming-r1/video/nvidia.o\n"
"/lib/modules/2.4.20-gaming-r1/kernel/fs/fat/fat.o\n"
"/lib/modules/2.4.20-gaming-r1/kernel/fs/vfat/vfat.o\n"
"/lib/modules/2.4.20-gaming-r1/kernel/fs/minix/minix.o\n"
"[listing \"snipped\" for brevity]\n"
msgstr ""

#. type: Content of: <guide><chapter><section><title>
#: en/articles/lpi-101-administration-p2.xml:1986
#, no-wrap
msgid "insmod vs. modprobe"
msgstr ""

#. type: Content of: <guide><chapter><section><body><p>
#: en/articles/lpi-101-administration-p2.xml:1990
#, no-wrap
msgid ""
"So, how does one load a module into a running kernel? One way is to use the\n"
"<c>insmod</c> command and specifying the full path to the module that you wish\n"
"to load:\n"
msgstr ""

#. type: Attribute 'caption' of: <guide><chapter><section><body><pre>
#: en/articles/lpi-101-administration-p2.xml:1995
#, no-wrap
msgid "using insmod"
msgstr ""

#. type: Content of: <guide><chapter><section><body><pre>
#: en/articles/lpi-101-administration-p2.xml:1996
#, no-wrap
msgid ""
"# <i>insmod /lib/modules/2.4.20-gaming-r1/kernel/fs/fat/fat.o</i>\n"
"# <i>lsmod | grep fat</i>\n"
"fat                    29272   0  (unused)\n"
msgstr ""

#. type: Content of: <guide><chapter><section><body><p>
#: en/articles/lpi-101-administration-p2.xml:2002
#, no-wrap
msgid ""
"However, one normally loads modules by using the <c>modprobe</c> command. One\n"
"of the nice things about the <c>modprobe</c> command is that it automatically\n"
"takes care of loading any dependent modules. Also, one doesn't need to specify\n"
"the path to the module you wish to load, nor does one specify the trailing\n"
"\".o\".\n"
msgstr ""

#. type: Attribute 'caption' of: <guide><chapter><section><body><pre>
#: en/articles/lpi-101-administration-p2.xml:2012
#: en/articles/lpi-101-administration-p2.xml:2019
#, no-wrap
msgid "rmmod and modprobe in action"
msgstr ""

#. type: Content of: <guide><chapter><section><body><p>
#: en/articles/lpi-101-administration-p2.xml:2016
#, no-wrap
msgid "Let's unload our \"fat.o\" module and load it using <c>modprobe</c>:\n"
msgstr ""

#. type: Content of: <guide><chapter><section><body><pre>
#: en/articles/lpi-101-administration-p2.xml:2020
#, no-wrap
msgid ""
"# <i>rmmod fat</i>\n"
"# <i>lsmod | grep fat</i>\n"
"# <i>modprobe fat</i>\n"
"# <i>lsmod | grep fat</i>\n"
"fat                    29272   0  (unused)\n"
msgstr ""

#. type: Content of: <guide><chapter><section><body><p>
#: en/articles/lpi-101-administration-p2.xml:2028
#, no-wrap
msgid ""
"As you can see, the <c>rmmod</c> command works similarly to modprobe, but has\n"
"the opposite effect -- it unloads the module you specify.\n"
msgstr ""

#. type: Content of: <guide><chapter><section><title>
#: en/articles/lpi-101-administration-p2.xml:2035
#, no-wrap
msgid "Your friend modinfo and modules.conf"
msgstr ""

#. type: Content of: <guide><chapter><section><body><p>
#: en/articles/lpi-101-administration-p2.xml:2039
#, no-wrap
msgid ""
"You can use the <c>modinfo</c> command to learn interesting things about your\n"
"favorite modules:\n"
msgstr ""

#. type: Attribute 'caption' of: <guide><chapter><section><body><pre>
#: en/articles/lpi-101-administration-p2.xml:2043
#, no-wrap
msgid "Using modinfo"
msgstr ""

#. type: Content of: <guide><chapter><section><body><pre>
#: en/articles/lpi-101-administration-p2.xml:2044
#, no-wrap
msgid ""
"# <i>modinfo fat</i>\n"
"filename:    /lib/modules/2.4.20-gaming-r1/kernel/fs/fat/fat.o\n"
"description: &lt;none&gt;\n"
"author:      &lt;none&gt;\n"
"license:     \"GPL\"\n"
msgstr ""

#. type: Content of: <guide><chapter><section><body><p>
#: en/articles/lpi-101-administration-p2.xml:2052
#, no-wrap
msgid ""
"And make special note of the <path>/etc/modules.conf</path> file. This file\n"
"contains configuration information for <c>modprobe</c>. It allows you to tweak\n"
"the functionality of <c>modprobe</c> by telling it to load modules before/after\n"
"loading others, run scripts before/after modules load, and more.\n"
msgstr ""

#. type: Content of: <guide><chapter><section><title>
#: en/articles/lpi-101-administration-p2.xml:2061
#, no-wrap
msgid "modules.conf gotchas"
msgstr ""

#. type: Content of: <guide><chapter><section><body><p>
#: en/articles/lpi-101-administration-p2.xml:2065
#, no-wrap
msgid ""
"The syntax and functionality of <path>modules.conf</path> is quite complicated,\n"
"and we won't go into its syntax now (type <c>man modules.conf</c> for all the\n"
"gory details), but here are some things that you *should* know about this file.\n"
msgstr ""

#. type: Content of: <guide><chapter><section><body><p>
#: en/articles/lpi-101-administration-p2.xml:2071
#, no-wrap
msgid ""
"For one, many distributions generate this file automatically from a bunch of\n"
"files in another directory, like <path>/etc/modules.d/</path>. For example,\n"
"Gentoo Linux has an <path>/etc/modules.d/</path> directory, and running the\n"
"<c>update-modules</c> command will take every file in\n"
"<path>/etc/modules.d/</path> and concatenate them to produce a new\n"
"<path>/etc/modules.conf</path>. Therefore, make your changes to the files in\n"
"<path>/etc/modules.d/</path> and run update-modules if you are using Gentoo. If\n"
"you are using Debian, the procedure is similar except that the directory is\n"
"called <path>/etc/modutils/</path>.\n"
msgstr ""

